animal.description:
Diagnosed with mast cell tumors. She was supposedly to be a short term hospice foster. But it has been almost 2 years since she was dumped at animal control and she is still doing great on meds (omeprazole, prednisone, Benadryl). Her previous life was one of severe neglect. She was used as a breeder and then discarded like trash. She is the sweetest girl and gets along with everyone. She gets a little grumpy if the other dogs try to take her food or if I'm eating. But that's understandable considering her background. She has so much love to give and would like a lap to snuggle in and gentle hands to pet her.

If you are interested in adopting, please cut and paste the link below to fill out an adoption application:

https://form.jotform.com/92916416469165

After the application is processed and approved, a home visit and meet and greet with the dogs will be scheduled. If there are any fencing issues, make sure that repairs are done prior to the home visit. MinPins are natural escape artists! Typically, the adoption is finalized the day after the home visit and meet and greet. Out of area adopters would need to drive/fly in to meet the dogs and adopt.

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 8/23/2017

Reason for being in rescue: Stray- nc shelter
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Ollie has no known medical issues but is very strong willed. He despises other dogs and cats and needs to be in a home where he does not have contact with other canines or cats. He will attack other dogs. It is sad because he was not like this originally but something changed.
Weight: 46 lbs
Height: 21" at the shoulder

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? Secure fence - prefer privacy please or a back yard that does not back up to a yard with a dog so he can play and not worry about the other dogs.

What kind of home would be best for me? Hmmm.. I'm really not hard to please. Just give me attention and let me lay around on the couch with you! I love people, I love living in a house and I love being part of your life. I am a lot of dog - you won't need another one if you have me.

Ollie is going to be amazing in the right hands. Our owner experince level for Ollie is an
8 - More than 10 years as dog owner and preferrably with a terrier breed. Has taken at least three professional training courses. Long history of superior vet care. No history of rehoming or rehoming only for serious lifestyle challenge, worked through reputable rescue to place and follows up.

What is my personality like? I'm Ollie Beckett and if my name wasn't already cute enough.. just look at my sweet face. I was found a stray in North Carolina and taken to a local shelter. I was actually just saved in the nick of time... I was making my way to be sent to doggie heaven until the lady walking me to "the room" saw my tail wag and it was all over from there. She begged and of course CPR said yes!

I'm a silly boy that loves all humans. I can't possibly give out enough hugs for everyone around here. I will love you through the good times, and bad times. I will be your best friend through it all, given the chance. I walk well on a leash but I love love love sniffing everything I can so please let's make some walks slow walks. I don't know any basic commands yet but I bet I could learn. One of my favorite things to do is roll around on the couch and nuzzle under every blanket I can get under. I love, and I love hard, Please take me home!

Update 6/18- I was returned to the rescue because I did not get along with some dogs that I have met. It was also said that I have separation anxiety and that I have lunged at people/cars going by. So far, the caregivers have not seen this behavior at the rescue either time I have been here.

How do I act when I first meet new people? friendly

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

My age: Estimated birth date 8/24/2016

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Atlas is ready to be the king of your world! This handsome young bridle boy is around 3.5 years old and happiest when he's running and playing fetch. Atlas is well trained and knows how to sit, shake, stay, lay down, wait, come, leave it and get up. Atlas is also muzzle trained, he prefers to wear this when meeting strangers or doing scary things like visiting the vet's office.

Atlas would thrive in an active home with adults only who are dog savvy and maintain a relatively quiet home life. We don't know all of his background, but we know that strangers in the home are scary to Atlas and he isn't sure if he's supposed to protect you from them or not! Atlas loves to play, so another playful dog in the home would make for a perfect match! Atlas is kennel and potty trained, and also loves to give kisses. A 4-6 foot high fenced in yard would be a dream come true for ol' Atlas, here he could run and play to his hearts content and maybe learn some more impressive commands with a little help from his new family.

If you are interested in learning more about Atlas please complete an adoption application for consideration at www.AdoptHope.org. The adoption fee for Atlas is $250 and includes his neuter, microchip, current vaccinations and preventatives as well as a FREE obedience class through Cedar Run in Hiawatha. Our adoption process includes reference and background checks, a vet check and home visit.

Here are some fun facts about Jack(son)! 
-Jackson knows sit, down and roll over. He is super smart and very eager to learn more.
-Jackson loves toys- balls, Kong’s, squeaky toys, you name it!! He can entertain himself for hours!

animal.description:
Please be aware that during COVID 19 social distancing regulations, we will NOT be placing Asher & Rolloe in a foster or forever home.  They are dogs with behavioral and fear issues, and we cannot simply "drop him off at your door".

Asher and Rollie will require multiple meetings with his handler at the home. His handler MUST be able to watch the interactions and advise foster or adopter  how to manage the dogs appropriately.

Please DO NOT send in an application for Asher & Rollie until COVID 19 resolved and we can go back to visiting fosters and adopters in their homes..

Thank you!

*****"********************"""*********

Rollie and Asher are best pals and can never be separated.. Both dogs were dumped in an abandoned gravel pit In Abbotsford about 3 years ago.  They were extremely fearful and hard to catch. 

Asher is an Australian terrier mix and is about 5 years old...Rollie is a chihuahua pug mix and he is about 7 years old.  

They have come a long way since they were caught years ago.  Both dogs have lots of fear issues and are not fully trusting of humans.  Asher has become somewhat friendly and loving now, but he still has initial fears with new people and new environments. Rollie is still not 100% trusting of his human counterparts but is not aggressive.  He does tend to follow Asher's lead.

Both dogs need a foster home to see how they will do in a home environment.  Moving them to a new environment will re trigger their fears/ptsd and they will regress after being moved..  it will take a few months for them to settle into a new routine with new people.  They need to be house trained. They have been good on leash but in quiet areas only.  High traffic areas would not be suitable or ideal for Asher and Rollie.  Noises such as cars and trucks would trigger their fears.  Lots of strange people walking passed in busy areas would send them over the roof. 

They should be in a home with a fully fenced, escape proof yard to ensure they can be house trained. Their leash training should also begin there. 

Neither dog has any basic obedience training, as we only worked on them learning to trust humans.  They should not be flooded or forced to do things most normal dogs would be doing such as going for walks on leash right away, no off leash dog parks.  Not taking them to busy functions, stores or areas.  

They have been good with small and large dogs.  And have left the cats alone. 

Absolutely NO children in the foster home due to them still having fear triggers. 

We are looking for a FOSTER HOME ONLY AT THIS TIME.  

No apartments.  Access to fully fenced yard escape proof yard is a must. (no exceptions) 

If you are interested in fostering please send us an email and we will have you complete the foster application and have an interview and a home visit  to ensure you have the experience and patience to work with our 2 special boys.

animal.description:
This is Ashima, a female, 26 lb, brindle and white terrier mix whose  estimated date of birth is June, 2016. Her name means "Limitless" however, this girl keeps finding herself in impossible situations that set her up to lose. 

Her people failed her. Ashima found herself pregnant and surrendered to a shelter, her chances of getting out were slim to begin with. Then she developed an upper respiratory infection and that took her situation from bad to worse. The transport leaving the state picked another dog over her and she was stuck waiting again. When ARF stopped by that day she jumped at the chain link and tried to get to us as fast as possible to give kisses. After all this time she had not given up hope, we knew she needed another chance.

Ashima is an happy, fun and active dog who would love to go running with an active person! She has healthy boundaries and an assertive personality because she knows what she likes and what she does not! Ashima is much too interested in cats and finds small children annoying so she would likely do best in a home as the only "child" or with another active dog about her size. Ashima is crate trained and would like a privacy fence since she is a gifted fence climber that finds chain link ones to be a good piece of exercise equipment ? Please help us find her a home where she can finally live up to her potential. Ashima may out of the shelter but now she needs someone to step up and help her live without the limits life keeps trying to impose on her!

Ashima has a $150.00 adoption fee plus the cost of 6 months of heart-worm prevention.  


Note: ARF reserves the right to deny any application that is deemed unsuitable for the animal. Please be aware that our animal adoptions are NOT on a first come- first serve basis. Our sole purpose is to find the best possible home for the animals that fall under our care. We do not ship our animals. All adopters are expected to come to Tulsa if approved.

For details on how to adopt please visit http://www.arftulsa.org/howtoadopt.html

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: A good fit with other dogs as long as they are not dominate/aggressive.

NO CHILDREN - NO CATS - NO OTHER DOGS IN THE HOME - EXPERIENCED OWNER TO BE ABLE TO CONTINUE TRAINING. FENCED IN YARD A MUST - NO ACCEPTIONS.

Kara is food & toy aggressive towards other dogs but is fine with other people. 

Absolutely no young children in the home and a physical fenced in yard is a must and is not negotiable.

Their foster mom has been working with them on training, they have come a very long way and an experienced adopter will need to continue working on socializing these two beautiful girls.

animal.description:
Lorelai came into us, pregnant, from a puppy mill that shut down. She was so young when she had her puppies - she was almost a puppy still herself. She came to us very skittish and shy and while she has come leaps and bounds in her foster home, her background of neglect from the puppy mill is coming with her. She can get scared in new situations and with new people and does take a bit to warm up to people. But once she does, she lets her personality shine, which is crazy, active, silly and smart and often mischievous. She knows not to jump on you to say hi, but sometimes she just cannot help it. She knows the garbage is off limits, but you know, sometimes there is just something so wonderful in there that she thinks she needs to bend the rules a bit. She loves toys, and stuffies are her favorites, but she still thinks eating them is a fun thing to do so only certain toys are Lorelai OK'd at this point. Because she thinks anything left out is hers, we do not want young children in the home. Toys and stuffed animals left out will be appropriated and eaten.

We are looking for a home for Lorelai that has lots of patience, understands that routine is the key to her comfort and that has at least one other dog for her to gain confidence and learn from. Now that her pups are adopted and in wonderful homes, it is her turn. She is not going to be a super easy dog at first but we guarantee that all the love you put into her will be given back tenfold.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website. HI! I'M ASHER! I love long walks and LOVE to play! First thing people and canines notice about me are my bright green eyes! Darn Im handsome! My foster parents tell me I am a good boy and notice when I first meet people I am a little timid and shy but I slowly warm up and love the attention and compliments that come thereafter. When I lived with my former dad, I wasnt well socialized and got hurt by two of my siblings, so, I get scared of other dogs when we go for our walks(I am dog reactive when I see a dog)and we are working on that! My foster family are working with me now on learning how to meet and greet new people and pets. Even though I get scared when I see other dogs, I LOVE my foster parents dogs! I LOVE to play with my foster mommy and her fur children(be part of the pack) just no rough play,makes me nervous. I am also told I think I am a lap dog and love to snuggle and get some lovin! My former owner told my foster mommy that I was his 'therapy' dog. I snuggled with my dad when he was having a hard day or suffering from ptsd. I AM a good boy, I just had a hard upbringing and just need some work with a professional trainer to work on my socialization skills and learning to greet new fur friends. As I said before, I get along well with my foster parents dogs but I met them slowly,after a couple of weeks with some training and now LOVE my brothers and sisters!I am not sure if I would do well with someone who has dogs, maybe if someone takes the time to work with me on slow greeting.. As for cats, I do not chase or show aggression to my foster moms cats but Im working on properly greeting them since Im excited to see them. I think I will do well with a cat/s that is used to dogs...I think a good mommy and/or daddy candidate would be someone who has experience with dogs and has time and patience to work with a trainer on my issues with interaction with other dogs. Ideally,someone who is home with me (I LOVE being with my human and prefer that to being alone) but I do well when at home alone too;someone who has time to be with and work with me and would be a strong handler..
Please contact app@aarfhouston.org for more information about this dog. You can apply online by clicking on Application . Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events. Thank you for considering a rescue! The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.
AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

Posted 6/29/18, and pictures updated 5/10/20 - Callan was surrendered on 4/11/18. An older woman contacted the Smith County, TX Shelter about her young dog. The officer who talked to her, called me to see if I could help, since the shelter cannot take owner surrenders. I had recently had some adoptions, so I told him that he caught me at a good time. He brought the young dog to me later that day, and I didn't get the dog's name from the home, so I named him Callan.

I took Callan to the Gresham Veterinary Hospital on 4/13/18 to get vaccinated, he was listed as a Doberman mix, 1.5 years old, weighed 44.6 pounds, and was neutered by Dehart Veterinary Services on 4/14/18.  As of 5/10/20, he weighs 54 pounds.

Callan is good with adults and children, loves to play with the other dogs, has a high pitch bark at times when he sees things like squirrels in the trees, is good on a leash, and crate trained.  He loves to be pet, and will put his head on my lap to get pet.  He requires a fenced yard, and is not an apartment dog.  He didn't like to be crated at night, but got better.  I eventually stopped putting him in a crate at night, since he does well outside at night.

Callan's adoption fee is $85. Anyone interested in adopting him, please e-mail me at TMSGriffith@aol.com.

animal.description:
LUCA
DOB: February 14, 2015*

Luca is one of those dogs whose picture you see online and fall so madly in love with him you think you couldn't love him anymore. Then you meet him, and your heart explodes. He is that loveable.

Luca is a little shy at first, he has had his heart broken by unworthy people in the past, so patience with him at first is the best way to win his heart. But once he warms up, you get the full Luca experience. He will adore you just as much as you adore him, 70 pounds of total adoration, devotion and kisses. Had a bad day? Luca can help. He can lounge around and watch a movie with you or lift your spirits with a little rousing game of fetch and tag in the backyard with his Kong. He will plop his big fat head in your lap, look up at you with those gorgeous green eyes and you can see how much he loves you and wants to make life better for you. This guy will touch your soul and you will know love.

His favorite toy is his Kong. When he is nervous it acts like a binky for him. He is very smart and listen well. He just wants to please and make his person happy. 

Luca is a Mastiff/Bully mix about 3 or 4 years old (as of 2018). He weighs in around 70 pounds, which is all solid muscle. He is neutered, current on vaccinations, microchipped, good with properly introduced dogs, but especially good with the ladies. His has beautiful green eyes and a shiny. gorgeous fawn colored coat with white markings. He hasn't had any prior experience with cats so we suggest a home without any feline companions, or maybe a very dog savvy cat. He is house trained, crate trained, good on a leash, knows basic obedience (but can have a bout of 'bully hearing' when sniffing something especially interesting in the yard lol), loves car rides and is an all around good dog. Because of his size, we recommend a home without small children. He can get very exuberant in his play and may accidentally knock small children down. We want both Luca and his new family to be happy so a home experienced with bully breeds is a must.

Adoption Process: Application, Interview, Homecheck
Adoption Fee: $250

This dog is located near Fresno, Ca

*Age is always a guess with rescue dogs but here at Paw Printz we believe everyone should have a birth day so when the vet guesses at their age, we work out what would be a good birthday for each dog and make it so!

Alexa, play Sugar Sugar by the Archies. Now that youve got that song playing in the background, youre in the proper zone to learn about the sweetest girl around, our very own Sugar!

Sugar really does have it all: the looks, the manners, and the drive to be the very best friend around. She successfully completed a three month board-and-train program at Golden Heart Canine where she was a star pupil, and those skills have stuck with her! She has fantastic leash manners and knows all the basic commands. An added bonus is that Sugar is very treat motivated, so shes always eager to learn new skills and tricks. If you need some proof, just ask her to shake! She also loves trying to chase bunnies so will do a great job of keeping your yard clear of intruders. Sugar is quite an active girl, and always smiles when shes out on walks and hikes. Peep her photos to see this sweet girl in her happy place out in the Colorado sun!

Sugar LOVES playing with other dogs, always asking permission and then approaching her fellow canines with many lady-like grunts to let you know that the wrestling match has begun. Because she is a little bit unaware of her size, we recommend a house that has no feline friends or other small mammals (including children!) right now.

Though Sugar is the biggest sweetheart, she had to overcome quite a past to reach this point. Sugar was adopted as a puppy and never socialized. She was returned to the rescue as a very shy, easily frightened adult who was slow to warm up to people. Although Sugar has improved her social butterfly status, she is still working through this timidness and so it will likely take more than one meet and greet before she will let her guard down to start becoming familiar and comfortable with you.

That being said, once Sugar comes out of her shell theres no putting her back in! She really makes you feel like the most important person on the planet whenever she sees you, even if you were only gone for 5 minutes. Sugar is looking for her people to share kisses with, grab a good belly rub from, and take some Colorado joyrides in the car. She reaches peak happiness when poking her head out the window feeling the wind rushing through her fur! If you can show her patience and take the necessary steps to help Sugar trust you, she will reward you with unending love and affection. Sugar is the candy girl, and cant wait to blast that tune with the windows down and her best friend by her side!

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration
	Deworming

Description:
Hi, I'm Rocco a handsome Chow mix rescued from a shelter. I was an owner surrender due to my owner moving and I couldn't go too. I was described by the shelter as being very sweet, very friendly and a favorite of volunteers. I'm grateful to C.A.R.L. for rescuing me before it was too late.

I've been lucky enough to be in a foster home since April 2020 where everyone is basically home all day. They've created an Instagram page just for me. rocco_rockz. They say I'm rather stiff in my back legs and I can't get in the car by myself or get up a full flight of stairs. I get to go on two walks a day. I need a home with no younger children. My foster family has a 16 and 17 year old who I do great with.

I love being with my people and don't enjoy being left alone. If one person leaves, I wait by the door and cry until they come back.

I'm dog reactive and would do best as the only dog in your home. I'm easier to control on walks with a harness. I need a home with no cats. I'm also a creature of habit so will do best with a set routine.

I hope you'll open your heart and home to wonderful me.

*Thank you to Sharon for sponsoring this wonderful dog and giving him the chance for a better life..

Additional information: *Housetrained *Needs home with no small children *Needs home with no dogs *Needs home with no cats *Current on shots

animal.description:
Sweet, silly Sassafras!   This lovely Cane Corso girl knows her forever family is out there somewhere. and Miss Sassy wants her new people to know these 10 things about her:

1.  I was treated terribly before I came to rescue.  The people at my old home would lock me in the house for weeks with just a pile of food, or tie me to the front porch for days, while they went off and did other things.  I was always hungry and always hurting.  I’m very lucky that my awful owners had responsible neighbors who didn’t stop calling the dog police until they came to get me.  

2.  When I got to the shelter, I was very scared and I got very sick.  I acted like a complete jerk to almost everyone, but the Bullpen saw right through my act and asked me to come to the sanctuary. 

3.  I am learning every day that people are good and that I can trust them.  My foster mom says I am making wonderful progress and I should be proud of myself, even if I am still a total grump when I meet new people.  

4.  When I see people that I know, I turn into a super wiggle-butt snuggle monster.  I can’t help myself.  I just want to be around them and play with toys with them and be petted.  I’m definitely one of the most affectionate dogs at the sanctuary.

5.  When I meet other dogs through the fence, I wag my tail at them, and I think I could happily live with an easy-going, big male dog if we were properly introduced.  Because I was so sick at the shelter, I wasn’t allowed to meet any other dogs, so I’m not sure how I feel about little and medium sized pups. 

6.  My kennel at the shelter was close to the pen where they keep goats and chickens, and I was generally oblivious.  When I see birds and squirrels and the occasional cat here at the sanctuary, I’m interested for a few seconds, but then I forget about them.

7.  My ideal home would be with an adults-only family that is willing to work with me on building confidence, and that doesn’t have many visitors to the house.  New people are scary to me, and when I’m afraid, I am not my best self.  

8.  I am really good on a leash, and will go into a crate, even if I don’t like it.  I know how to use a dog door and will sit when you tell me.  I do, however, have a bad habit of jumping up to get your attention, and I need my forever family to keep working with me to curb the behavior.

 9.  My back end is a little funny.  There, I said it.  It’s really only noticeable when I sit down, but it’s hard to miss. The veterinarian took x-rays of my legs and pelvis but couldn’t find anything that would really explain it.  I have no trouble getting around, but the Bullpen thought it was best to start me on a daily anti-inflammatory, which I take without complaint.  

10.   I am current on vaccinations, microchipped, and spayed.  I’ve started heartworm treatment, and will come with all the medicine needed to complete it at my new home.

Ready to give Sassy the forever home of her dreams?  Fill out our Adoption Application, located at bullpenrescue.org under the 'work with us' tab. We highly recommend that our potential adopters fill out an online application as soon as possible, as it greatly expedites the process of finding the right dog for your situation.  

Our dogs are available for adoption nationwide but preference is given to adopters willing to do an in-person meeting.  Please understand that our dogs are not adopted on a first-come, first-serve basis, but rather we strive for a "perfect placement" so we know that they will not be failed again.

animal.description:
WHERE IS THIS DOG NOW ?- This pet is currently located in foster in Belgrave

**ALL ABOUT  JASMINE  **
Born approx 2017.
She was said to be 1 year old on intake then and she had just had pups. So she was about 3 in 2020.
Last weigh-in she was 38 lbs.

PEOPLE SKILLS -
She initially only trusted the Foster who got her out of a trailer she was living in with 32 others mid June 2018.

She is still a very scared girl with strangers.
She will bite IF her space and cues are not respected. 
This is a fear-defensive response in order to set boundaries that are not being respected.

KIDS -
She would not suit a home with infants/toddlers/kids.

VISITORS -
She does not prefer visitors in the home.

CATS -
She is fostered with cats.

DOGS -
She is fostered with her brother who was adopted by the foster - he is half her size.

Foster says that she prefers to play with the bigger dogs and can play rough, so a smaller dog is not an appropriate match for her play style. ie no Yorkies please. 
She needs a home with dogs used to playing like she prefers.

Since she loves to play with certain other dogs in her foster home she MUST have one in her adoptive home. 

VEHICLES -
She likes car rides with her foster Mom.

HER HISTORY -
Mid June 2018 we took in 28 out of a trailer after owners left them in 40 degree heat for 4 days. 

The owners had done this before and thankfully a foster was able to remove the majority, after the O.P.P attended the scene.

With 33 dogs/pups total in the camping trailer - every single female already had pups or was pregnant despite being said to be only 12-18 months old.

There was no way to know who is who's father.

There was no way to know the breeds of the litters.

Jasmine is a mix breed.

She even took on another Mother's son to surrogate.

They had no food in the camping trailer and the owners admitted when this happened that they would feed them noodles.

Her 3 boys consisted of Wilson, Mulligan and Bogey.

The middle litter of 2 boys, consisted of Gizmo and Sprocket.

She raised Sprocket as her own.

Many of the pups had the shihtzu underbite.

When she went to be spayed the vet found a large scar up her stomach and the owner's had said they had never been vetted so the vet's believe the owner's did a home c-section on her.

REQUIREMENTS -
She needs fear defensive experienced adopters, adults ONLY no children.
She needs a home with no visitors.
She would need a secure yard to enjoy and fear reactive dog experience.
She would need an active canine playmate in the home.

If your home has few to no visitors, has rescue savvy adults, and sounds compatible to her needs -
You can apply online at www.adoptapet.lucknow.on.ca 

Her adoption fee-  $500 with spay/painkiller, dewormer, vaccs, parasite prevention

Once we review your application then your family and existing dog can come and meet and see if they are the match you are looking for.

** WE DO NOT ADOPT OUT OF ONTARIO **

THANK YOU FOR YOUR INTEREST IN ADOPTING A RESCUE DOG - PLEASE READ THIS ENTIRE FEED TO ANSWER ALL YOUR QUESTIONS 
**BASIC INQUIRIES ASKING QUESTIONS THAT ARE PROVIDED WILL NOT BE ANSWERED. ** WE ARE ALL VOLUNTEERS WHO HAVE EXISTING PETS/ FAMILY/ PAYING JOBS. OUR TIME IS IN SHORT SUPPLY AND WE APPRECIATE YOUR UNDERSTANDING
******************************************************

*** HOW IT WORKS - ADOPTION INFORMATION **** 
***ONLY RECEIVED & APPROVED APPLICATIONS WILL BE CONSIDERED FOR A VIEWING..-**No exceptions  **
 Do not ask to pop by to view a dog - it will be declined. Our dogs are in various locations in foster homes. Viewings are arranged with volunteers ,around rescue work, reg jobs and family  and only offered to an approved app to ensure its a possible fit for the dog and applicant and to not waste anyone's time.

All info on adoption process/ policies can be accessed at www.adoptapet,lucknow.on.ca 
**.Applications 
http://www.adoptapet.lucknow.on.ca/applications.html--This is a MS Word copy of our application.
It can be completed, saved and emailed back to the rescue at 
petrescue@hurontel.on.ca . 

1. We require a fully filled app to be considered as a possible home
2. Only the approved app will be permitted a viewing with the pet ** in the foster home 3. ALL family members MUST meet the dog ** in the foster home** .
4. Any existing pets MUST attend the meet/ greet with the dog ** at the foster home ** .
5. A home visit must be completed as part of the adoption process after the initial viewing by a rescue representative.
This is not a replacement of the meet/ greet at the Foster home.
6. We do not adopt outside of ONTARIO . 
7. We do not deliver dogs. If and once the adoption process is approved and complete the dog must be picked up at the foster home 

If you have any difficulties with the various application options please let us know @ petrescue@hurontel.on.ca

*********************************************************************************************
IF YOU THINK THIS DOG WOULD BE A GOOD ADDITION TO YOUR HOME AND YOUR ENTIRE HUMAN AND CANINE FAMILY CAN ATTEND THIS DOG'S FOSTER HOME THEN PLEASE FEEL FREE TO SEND IN AN APPLICATION

animal.description:
WE ARE IN URGENT NEED OF FOSTER HOMES

WHY DOES UGLY MUTTS NEED FOSTER HOMES?

Foster families are the very backbone of Ugly Mutts Dog Rescue.  As we do not have a physical shelter, we depend on caring individuals to open their hearts and their homes to care for and maintain the rescued dogs until they can be rehomed with loving, committed adopters.

WHY SHOULD I FOSTER A DOG?

Fostering a dog is one of the most rewarding experiences you can have (other than adopting of course).  By caring for an animal in need temporarily in your home:

You are saving the life of a deserving dog that might otherwise be euthanized due to no fault of their own.
You give the dog the time they need to be ready for adoption.
You help us learn more about the dog which helps ensure they end up in the best home possible.
You help with socializing the dog to a home environment, people and other pets.
WHAT DOES FOSTERING A DOG FOR UGLY MUTTS DOG RESCUE INVOLVE?

When you agree to foster a dog, you agree to take responsibility for a homeless pet and give him or her love, care and attention, until he or she is adopted.  All the food, supplies and vetting are provided by the Rescue.

You will receive an Ugly Mutts Foster Guide which will give you informative information on bringing your foster dog home, and tips on feeding and training.  As well, you will have access to our team of Rescue Coordinators for any additional help you need along the way.

All of the dogs you foster will have been chosen based on your requirements, your family situation, and your abilities, to ensure there is an easy transition into your home.

HOW DO I SIGN UP TO FOSTER FOR UGLY MUTTS?

Complete our Foster Application online!  One of our Rescue Coordinators will be in touch ASAP.

http://www.uglymuttsdogrescue.com/get-involved/become-a-foster-parent/foster-application-2/

animal.description: Quinn is approximately 6 to 7 years old. He has been at ARCC since May 2018. This poor guy was found near Mt. Blanco, Texas with a mouth and face full of porcupine quills and starving. A farmer spotted him and alerted us to his plight. We found him under a trailer in a very rural area with no houses or people nearby. We caught this sweet boy and took him to our vet immediately. He recovered nicely and gained all his weight back. He has been neutered, vetted, and microchipped. While Quinn was recovering, he got to spend time in a foster home with cats. He was curious but never showed any aggression. Since that time he has been housed at our kennels. Quinn has one female fur-friend that he plays with in the play yard. Her name is Trixie. Quinn is okay with some young puppies but not older dogs, or other large dogs. Quinn would love a home by himself or even with Trixie. This guy has TONS of energy and loves to get out and run and zoom around the play yard. He is very strong so a home with small children would not be recommended. He would do great with older kids. Please come meet Quinn! He is always overlooked. He is a kennel favorite!

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Addy! Here is what would work best for me in my new home:

-Personality: Goofy, exuberant, playful, loyal
-Can Live with Kids: Ages 16+
-Can Live with Cats: No, I like to chase cats and small animals.
-Can Live with Dogs: Maybe another tolerant adult dog! I'll have to meet any potential canine housemates first to make sure we're a good match.
-Can do Apartment Living: No - Addy would thrive in a home with a large yard where she doesn't have to worry about lots of neighbors walking by.
-Potty Trained: Yes
-Bite History: No, but history with fear of strangers.
-Positive Reward Based Obedience Classes Required: Yes, at least one private lesson. 
-Leash Trained: Yes
-Energy Level: Medium/high
-Needs Medical Procedure Before Going Home: No
-Additional Information: Addy is a silly dog who loves to play! Addy may have at one point enjoyed being a hiking or jogging buddy, but days of high impact or strenuous exercise are behind her. She has some stiffness in her limbs due to a cruciate injury and will need a milder exercise routine for management, ideally under the guidance of a vet. She would benefit from a continued high quality, low calorie diet to help her lose some weight and reduce stress on her limbs. In lieu of heavy physical exercise, Addy would benefit from extra mental stimulation - food puzzles, hide and seek, trick training - with her future adopter. Addy does have a history of fearfulness with strangers, so she will need a patient household willing to work with and manage her quirks. If you're looking for a snuggle buddy extraordinaire, fill out an application to meet Addy today!

animal.description:
Posted 6/19/18, and pictures taken 4/9/18 - Louise came from the Smith County, TX Shelter on 4/9/18. I had a few adoptions at that time, so I had space to tag some dogs from the shelter. I asked who had been there the longest, and needed out. Immediately I was told Louise and Sarge.

Louise has joined what I call my yard dogs that get to run the fenced in area of our property instead of going in a large dog pen, and goes in a crate at night. She barked a lot at first and doesn't always like to go in the crate, but is doing much better now. She still gets anxious to get out in the morning. She is good on a leash, good around adults and children, and LOVES getting in our water tubs.

Louise was picked up on FM 2767 and Greenwood on 3/7/18 weighing 73 pounds, heartworm positive, estimated to be 6 years old, and was not doing well being in the kennels. I had her spayed on 4/14/18, and she is on Ivomec for heartworm prevention, which will eventually help to kill the heartworms she has.

Louise's adoption fee is $85. Anyone interested in adopting her can e-mail me at TMSGriffith@aol.com.

animal.description:
Titan is a petite brindle boy with lots of love to give.  He loves kids but is an excited jumper so they need to be able to withstand his enthusiasm, and with a slow introduction to dogs, he has done well. If a dog is dominant or aggressive, he tends to react in that manner as well. He is altogether a wonderful dog. He's excelled well with his foster family and neighbors kids.

He loves toys and blankets and pillows are his thing.He has a  pillow like dog bed  and he loves it. Put a blanket on it and he's set or if he's on the couch, he puts his head on the pillow and sleeps like a human. 

Titan is super laid back, yet will go on walks or run around the yard or play with toys whenever his human wants. He's not a needy dog at all unless his water bowl is empty.  Then he will push it around my kitchen floor to get your attention 

When he is fed, he sits and waits patiently until his food is mixed and his bowl is placed down in front of him.  He does need some help in the walking on a leash with harness department.  He is motivated to learn with treats, so be sure to have plenty on hand, just please make sure there is no duck in his food or treats.  He does love to pass the time chewing on Nylabones.

Titan is house broken and is crate trained.  He is a smart, loving boy and will always let you know he loves you by nudging you with his nose, or a gentle headbutt.

 He has some separation anxiety and is on medication to control it. He struggles in the cage due to his anxiety, but when left out with his fur siblings, he does amazing. 

To learn more contact us at adoption@ihadro.org or apply today at www.ihadro.org!  Thank you for your interest.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Titan is good with other dogs, but may become dominant or aggressive if they display that behavior.  He is NOT cat or other small animal approved.  He needs to be around older kids who are able to withstand his excited jumping!

animal.description:
Tip: 5 yr Male BC/Aussie
Activity Level: Sports Companion/Active Companion
Diet: Balanced Raw Diet & Veggies
Special Talent: Sit Pretty w Front Paw Balance; Clicker Trained/Responsive/Whistle Responsive
Training: Heavy Socialization/Fear w Positive Boundaries
Experienced Dog/BC Owner Potentials
Tip is a striking boy that is a more private dog with strangers and affection.  Once he feels comfortable he will open up his trust, really enjoy his time with his people and is super smart.  He is ready to bound outside for fun times or leash activities. He needs lots of room to run and play with a 6 foot wooden fence and he can be overly stimulated using his herding mouth; tricks and redirection help this young man know the direction his human is asking for. He does focus on balls as he runs and explores things. He is easy on the leash but strong if something catches his interest and is totally excited when we run and play in a few hill hike/bike trails enjoying commands for jogging as well.  Tip is more private about his comfort level for love/petting and is working on this as he does enjoy our fun hugs and makes eye contact.  Tip is looking for an experienced dog person who understands the sensitivities of the Border Collie.  His litter came to my rescue July 4th 2014 at 4 months of age which is a prime life experience for any dog.  Tip overcame a lot of fears and had some imprinting from the owner reaching/grabbing. All the 8 puppies were running free on her 3 acres in Louisiana absorbing all sounds and movements of life, pretty dang scary for young herders.  He is still learning about strangers and how they should approach him for the best positive experience.  He is not suitable for cats or children/grandchildren as he is scared of fast movements and can fear bark. He would benefit from another dog in his home that is on his activity level and enjoy fun BC/Aussie play or play dates with dogs he’s met on leash walks. He crates nicely with a break during a work day, a 6 foot fence is required, and owners that follow his diet as his colon is super sensitive. All of his training/diet have been laid out for the next journey in his life! If an out of area applicant would be a potential match it is required they come to Houston to meet Tip and potentially stay a few days to further the matching process

Augie Doggie was unfortunately abandoned in a pen when his owners moved away, but he is now living the good life & learning how to be the perfect inside pet.  Augie is considered a high energy dog, would do best with a privacy fenced yard and is not suited for apartment living.    

Augie is a busy boy, always busy, busy, but can entertain himself with his toys.  Augie is dog friendly, but chooses his friends carefully.  

What's the down side of Augie?  He has extremely HIGH prey drive towards cats and any small animals.  He is not suited for a home where he could jump a fence to get at small animals which is why a privacy fence would be best.  Augie will surely entertain you if you are looking for a high energy, playful dog .

animal.description:
Hidey ho, my human friends! I'm Cress, a 2-year-old pittie mix looking for my purpose in life. Oh, and a home, I'm also looking for a home. More specifically, I'm looking for an active home that will give me a job to do. Not like a paying job, mind you! I'm thinking more along the lines of a volunteer job. For example, want to fetch balls? I'm your girl! Want to play frisbee? That's me! How about running? I'm down with that! Want to play hide and seek with treats? I'm all in! You see, I have high energy and drive and need mental and physical exercise to keep me healthy and happy.

Once I'm done with my "job" I settle in for some love and affection. I'm a really good student if you give me consistent training. I already know "sit" and am a good treat taker. As a bonus, I seem to like other dogs, with the proper introduction. (You just can't rush finding the right friends -- am I right?)

Think we might be a good match? Call or text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387 for more information and to set up a meeting with me!

Please contact The Pet Connection if you can foster, adopt, or sponsor a special needs dog or cat. 913-671-7387 Text. Www.thepetconnection.net.

animal.description:
My name is Mikos, and I'm going to take a chance on you! That's because I know someone is out there looking for a "special" dog like me. Maybe there's someone who has a 'thing" for older women or someone who loves the quiet of a senior companion. Or perhaps there is someone who understands getting old isn't for sissies.

This almost 10-year-old, 55-pound, female Golden Retriever mix has a smile as wide as Moon River and a heart as big as Texas. And Mikos has become a sweet, happy dog under the care of her foster family.

Mikos is a regal lady who is house trained (but has occasional accidents due to her age). And this "golden girl" is quiet...none of that barking or growling nonsense.

Mikos's foster mom can tell you all about Mikos and her age-related limitations. For example, Mikos has arthritis that comes with age. But with pain medication, laser treatments, and dog food specifically for joint improvement, she is doing well. She does need to avoid stairs, but she really enjoys short leash walks.

Mikos is the perfect partner for Netflix nights, crafting projects, gardening, sudoku, and culinary creations...just no rock climbing. And by the way, fireworks, thunderstorms, and doorbells don't phase Mikos because she can't hear. Mikos also gets along with everyone, except cats, we aren't sure about cats.

You can apply to adopt Mikos by completing an online adoption application. Come and meet this "golden girl."

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online at http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-forms

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

Please be sure to like our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/angelsrescue.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Bandit was picked up as a stray in rural Oklahoma. He appears to have had NO contact with humans before landing in the shelter. We have been working to gain his trust, and he has made a LOT of progress, but he is still very shy meeting new people.

Bandit gets along really well with other dogs, and is very playful. He has learned to walk nicely on a leash, and does well walking on a coupler with another dog. He seems to prefer sleeping in the crate, and will go to bed on his own at the end of the day.

Our hope is that with continued practice, Bandit will become more trusting of humans. He really seems to enjoy it when his foster family pets him and brushes his lovely coat -- he just soaks up the attention as though making up for lost time. We feel sure that Bandit will come around, but it will take a very patient, gentle adopter.

Bandit has been neutered, vaccinated, and microchipped, so he is ready to find a forever home. If you are ready to commit to spending at least 3 months earning Bandit's trust, please visit our website to learn more about our adoption process and complete an application: https://www.bluebonnetrescue.org/info/adoption

True loves nothing more than meeting people and spreading happiness. Being a shop or office dog would probably be his dream come true. He adores kids, is great with other dogs, gets long with cats, potbellied pigs and livestock, and has become a registered therapy dog. He enjoys walks, occasional hikes, and loves toys and the snow. He thinks visiting his foster mom’s brother’s family, with two kids and lots of people coming and going, is fabulously fun. True’s perfect family is out there, and his foster mom will be accepting applications for those who are looking for an incredibly special little guy who brings joy to everyone he meets. animal.description:
Meet Meimei
Make A Difference in your Community - Adopt a Shelter Dog! Would you like to foster a Shelter Survivor? For more information, visit us at www.sheltersurvivors.com

UPDATE:  After taking Meimei to the vet for extensive testing, we were very sad to find out that Meimei is in Stage 3 kidney disease. This was not the prognosis that we were hoping for. Meimei will now go from being a special needs case to a hospice case. Meimei's foster family has committed to keeping her comfortable for as long as possible; Meimei will remain in their care until her journey has ended. We will continue to manage Meimei's disease with prescription food, supplements, and medication. Most of all, we will spoil Meimei with endless love, cuddles, and comfort. She's a special little girl and we are heartbroken over her diagnosis. If you are interested in donating towards Meimei's care, you can do that by going to www.sheltersurvivors.com and clicking on the "Donate" button; or by going to the “How To Help” page to send a donation by mail. Thank you so much for your continued support.

Meimei's story:
Meet sweet Meimei! She is a Shih Zhu mix and about 8 years old. This 12 pound girl ended up in the shelter when her owner had to move. Meimei was devastated since that was the only home she had ever known. She had been with her person since she was 8 weeks old. Not only was Meimei stressed, she also suffered from allergies and began to lose her hair. When one of our volunteers saw Meimei’s sad little eyes and itchy skin, we knew that Meimei needed our help. After we got Meimei under our care, we found out that Meimei is showing early signs of kidney disease. We are in the process of completing extensive testing to see what stage she is in. We believe we have caught this early so we are hoping that she has many more wonderful years to be the loving and playful girl that we see everyday! The only symptoms she is showing at this point is the need to urinate more often and she can be very thirsty at times. Her appetite is great and she is active and playful! 
Although Meimei’s world has been turned upside down, she holds no grudges. She happily greets everyone she meets (men, women, and children). She enjoys going for several walks each day, and she loves snuggling next to her people. Meimei often looks up at her foster mom with her big and round thankful eyes. This look will make your heart melt. When she falls asleep, you will hear this cute little snore. Meimei doesn’t mind spending time in her crate while her foster family is at work. She greets dogs nicely and is fine living with the calm, larger dogs in her foster home.
When we picked Meimei up at the shelter, she had pink and itchy skin. We took her to the vet right away to see what was going on with her. It was determined that she has allergies that simply got out of control. Her ears were extremely infected (which we medicated); she needed medicine for her eyes; she needed allergy medicine, and a few baths a week to help soothe her skin. We noticed such a great improvement the very next day! Her hair is beginning to grow back very nicely. This will likely need to be managed for the rest of Meimei’s life.  And now she also has the kidney disease that also will need to be managed. As long as her new owner pays attention to her medical needs, she should live a happy and fulfilling life.  While Meimei is mostly housebroken, we sometimes use a diaper when she is roaming around at home, just in case she needs to go and we don't see her signal to go out. She is able to make it through the night without a diaper. We only use the diaper if we are preoccupied and can't keep a close eye on her for that moment while we are at home. Through all of this, Meimei has allowed all handling without any problems. She is a trooper! She’s just so happy to be in a home and loved again.

  
To adopt Meimei, please complete our online dog application  http://www.sheltersurvivors.com/application.html and return it to sheltersurvivors@live.com. Or go to sheltersurvivors.com , click on the home page, look for "Application" at the top of the home page, complete the application and hit the submit button once you have completed the application in its entirety. This will expedite the adoption process.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please contact Lynn & Cedric (lynnwelcomesyouhome@gmail.com) for more information about this pet. All of our dogs and cats are in foster homes and we have no paid staff. If you have questions concerning a specific animal, PLEASE fill out an application and the foster parent will be in touch. We will not arrange any home visits with any of our dogs and cats until your application is processed. Please understand our foster parents are precious to our 2nd Chance family; without them we cannot function, so we do our best to not burden them with multiple appointments. Our foster parents will choose their top 3 applications and arrange home visits with these applicants. The adopter will be chosen at that time. The process can take anywhere from a week to a month. We want to make sure our little furry ones are placed in their 'forever home' and never have to go through a rehoming again! If "CUDDLING" was an Olympic sport - Emma would win "GOLD"
Emma was adopted and lived in her forever home for 2 years. She lived with 2 other dogs without ANY incidents but one day her mom went to work and when she came home one of the dogs had been attacked and even though the vet tried to save it the dog was in shock and had to be given wings.No one witnessed the attack so there is no way of knowing for sure it was Emma but she had blood on her and scratches so it is assumed it was her. Therefore, even though the owner loved her she was not comfortable having her in their home with her other dog so sweet Emma is looking for her new FUREVER home.To be on the safe side we are looking for a home where she can be the only dog. She does well around other dogs at events but for Emmas sake we do not want to put her in a situation again that could go wrong because then she would have to be put down and that would be 'just wrong'. She is so loving and sweet and wants nothing more than to be with 'her person'.
Please fill out an adoption application:
Adoption application (Dog)
Adoption Application (Cat)

Please understand we do not adopt out dogs to
families with children under the age of 5. We do not adopt dogs to renters. Some dogs will have fence requirements while others may not.

A pet is a lifetime commitment. The dogs and cats in our system find themselves there, for the most part, because their humans did not have the same loyalty to them as they did to their owners. We do not take the adoption process lightly, and will do everything in our power to make sure the animal is placed correctly the first time around for your sake and theirs. Thank you for choosing to adopt not shop!

animal.description:
Look up ageless in the dictionary and you might just find a picture of LAILA. Laila is a stunning 13 years young beauty who doesn't seem to know she's a senior. This vivacious lady loves hiking, long walks (multiple times a day if you'll oblige), and running zoomies between head scratches, sunbathing, and perching on her fort. Her zest for an adventurist life knows no bound!

Laila can be touch sensitive but beneath that wild child exterior, she just wants to be loved and pampered like the queen she is. She was rescued from South LA shelter back in 2018 and has celebrated multiple New Years, Valentine's, Halloweens, Thanksgivings, and Christmases with us. We're hoping this is the year she lands herself an adoring family and warm home to call her own.

Laila is house-trained and crate-trained. We recommend a home without other pets and she would do best with older children (high school age or older).

animal.description:
CLARK IS IN A FOSTER HOME.  

Date of birth: 3/2016

8/17/2020:  Clark is a super cute Hound/Lab mix.  He’s 4 years old and weighs about 60 lbs, Clark is a very friendly guy. He’s sweet natured, energetic and smart.  He likes treats and sits nicely.  He’d be a great companion for an active person and we’d  like to place him in a home with a fenced yard.  He wouldn’t be a good mach for apartment living.  He is house trained.

• Clark loves kids but he tends to get too rough with them. He'd be fine with teenagers who are comfortable with a fairly large dog who can get rambunctious.

Clark is living in a foster home. Here's what his foster mom has to say about him:

• He is high-energy and needs walks and/or yard playtime every day

• Loves to play fetch. Loves toys in general and has taken to hiding and pretend "burying" in the house the ones he likes the most to keep them safe.

• Feels that affection should go both ways and wants to lick your face while he is being petted

• Frequently demands belly rubs

• Will nap on the couch with you and is an excellent cuddler.

• Knows sit, is working on "Off".

• Plays rough and is still working on not playbiting and jumping when he gets excited. 

• Follows sun spots around the house to laze in them.

• Loves being on the couch.

• Makes the cutest little grunting sounds. We call them his buffalo noises, and he does them when happy or when he wants something.

• Clark likes most other dogs and wants to play, but he comes on very strong when he meets dogs to play and we've found that most dogs are not happy about that.  If you have a dog we’d ask you to make an appointment to bring your dog in to meet Clark to see if they could be buddies.  

• Clark does need a home without cats.

When Clark came to us he had some pretty awful wounds on his left leg and shoulder area that needed medical care.  He’s all healed up now and doing fine.  He’s also been neutered, vaccinated, microchipped and tested for heartworms. 

MORE ON ADOPTING OUR DOGS... 

> COVID-19 UPDATE: PLEASE SUBMIT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION AND A MEMBER OF OUR ADOPTIONS TEAM WILL REACH OUT TO YOU. Please visit our web site at HSGKC.ORG for an adoption application, our current COVID-19 adoption protocol, and other adoption info.  

> If you decide you'd like to adopt one of the pets you meet, we reserve the pet for you but we generally don't send the pet home with you that day. We’ll instead schedule a pick up date and time that’s convenient for you.   

> Our goal is to send you home with a healthy pet and any information and support you may need to help your new pet adjust to his or her new home.  All of our dogs & puppies have been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, treated for fleas & ticks, tested for heartworms (7 mo. and over), and are on monthly heartworm preventative. Puppies who are too young to receive all the necessary puppy boosters and/or first rabies shot may be brought back to us for those vaccines at no extra charge. You will also receive a leash, collar, coupons for pet supplies and services, toys, and educational materials. And we'll give your dog a bath before he or she goes home! 

> Please note that we prefer and may require a fenced yard for many of our dogs.  Exceptions are made on an individual basis depending on the dog's needs, the person's dog experience, the dog's and person's activity levels, home environment and other factors. 

Thank you for searching for a shelter pet!

Dog Adoption Contact Info:
Email: christine@hsgkc.org
Phone: 913.596.1000 ext. 113
http://hsgkc.org

From Star's dad, "Star is a great dog and I would love to keep her if my circumstances were different. Without going into details, it is just not in the cards for me to be able to keep her. Everyone that has looked after her for me have loved her and say how great she is.

She is great on walks, short runs, and hikes. She loves to cuddle and she sleeps in my bed. She sits on command and will come when I call her. She knows 'paw', 'other paw', 'sit', 'lay down' (kinda), 'roll over' (with a lot of treat incentive and some assistance). She is very good about only going to the bathroom outside. What dog doesn't have the occasional accident? She has not chewed or destroyed anything in the house.

She loves that ice cream for dogs and denta stix. She loves tug-o-war and running around, being chased and just playing. She always has the biggest smile and I will miss her so much."

Inquire about Star today

animal.description:
I am ALEXI. If you're in the Seattle / greater Seattle area, please keep reading! If you have a big heart and love cuddles, I could be the one for you! 

I am a cute terrier mix and maybe Berger Picard (around 10kg and 3.5 years old) and if you take a look into my deep brown eyes and my large muppet ears, you might quickly fall in love. We are looking to keep me in the Seattle / North Seattle area, as I'm really bonded to my foster Mom, and would need a somewhat slow transition. Also, you could think of adopting me as possibly a part time share, my foster Mom would like to stay in my life, help out and dog sit, if that would be okay with you. Feel free to reach out for more information if you're truly interested, and you can chat with my current Mama. You can contact us through this rescue group or even send my foster Mom a message on my Instagram account - info below.

I was found by some kind people in an abandoned building, paralyzed in all four of my limbs. - Trust me, I'm a survivor! 

The good news - I am now in a loving foster home, just North of Seattle, and have had an MRI. My c5-c6 is injured, which has caused paralysis in my four limbs. My foster mama has done a tremendous amount of work with me to make me stronger.  At this point I can not sit, stand or walk by myself and my bladder gets expressed about 4 times a day. I don't wear diapers, and I have a normal 2x daily bowel movement. I'm one of the few paralyzed dogs that doesn't need to wear diapers! It's a good idea to get my urine tested every few months, since paralyzed dogs are prone to UTIs. I've only had one since I arrived a year ago. Since the time I've been in foster care, my whole body has become stronger. Six months after I arrived here, my back legs started to "wake up," it was amazing! I now go on daily walks / tows in my cart (see my videos, or check out my IG account). Once my cart starts to get pulled in a forward motion, my rear legs follow. Sometimes they want to collapse, but my human picks them up a bit and I'm ready to walk again! Currently I walk 1/4-1/2 a mile daily, sometimes more! I can't steer very well, because of my injury I tend to go left quite often. I move my front shoulders, but my front paws haven't woke up yet, but they are getting stronger. My days consist of cart walks, park visits, exercises, cuddles and snoozing. Once I get my walk, I'm usually ready for cuddles and a nap. I LOVE to take naps with my human.

 You may follow along my adventures here, which I now share with my foster sibling who was also rescued from this organization: https://www.instagram.com/rescuedgypsy/

People have started a go fund me page to help off set the cost of my rehab, as it has become quite expensive.  http://www.gofundme.com/help-alexi  

I also now have an Amazon.com wish list of my very own! https://amzn.to/2I3kT9v 

 I always so excited to go outside, and enjoy the fresh air! Sometimes that is in my cart, or my special backpack. Every time my human comes to give me love I do the wiggles and sometimes I sing to her.

I know it will take a special person to give me a forever home, but I believe this world is full of special people. I already found one of them and she's my foster mom. If dreams come true, my next special person is reading this right now and lives close to my foster family! I'd love a family who has a nice doggy friend for me, and someone who is home often. I like to be around my humans, in the same room, and outside on adventures. My forever human is someone who is physically fit and that will continue. If you live near me, my current Mama will go through my routines with you, including my favorite places to visit. 

I live with two cats, sometimes I'm not bothered by them, but sometimes I growl and bark (can you blame me, I am part terrier). I've met some children and do great sometimes. Other times I see them and I bark and growl. I do think I'd prefer a home without small children, and any older children need to be kind, gentle and patient. Once I know you, and you sit and give me treats for a couple of minutes I earn your trust. When I'm out on my walks in my cart, I very rarely bark, though I will do a high pitch happy bark when I see a dog that peeks my interest! I would thrive to be in a home with another gentle and playful dog. Having another loving dog around really has helped my motivation and my happiness. I am also not neutered and for now need to stay that way. I need my hormones to help me get stronger. 

I know it will take a special person to give me a forever home, but I believe you are out there somewhere and when we find each other both our lives will grow bigger with love.

Check out some of my videos!

https://youtu.be/fyHxK46lYus

https://youtu.be/BTeiM69_0Mc

https://youtu.be/Tk-eEaSbTSo

https://youtu.be/hFDEZ-8785Q

https://youtu.be/EKcn71KzIBU

https://youtu.be/sLwFCahPLWw

https://youtu.be/H97s9_hU6RM

I have been vaccinated and micro chipped.

My adoption fee is $300. 



Disclaimer: It is important for all applicants to visit our website, http://www.lovedatlastdogrescue.ca/adopting/ and read about Loved at Last Dog Rescue.

Information included in the profile is provided to us from the international rescuer or local fosters. LALDR does not have access to overseas dogs and cannot always verify the accuracy of their descriptions. Every dog is an individual and can act differently in different situations based on the person adopting them and the environment in which they live.

The age and breed of a dog is usually an educated guess, so we are not able to guarantee the accuracy of age or breed of our dogs.

Normally, we will not approve adoptions to homes with children under 12 years of age. More information can be found on our website.
My adoption fee is $300.

animal.description:
My name is Lily

I arrived at PATCH Rescue June 1, 2018 after being turned in by my former owners who fell on hard times and had to leave me behind as they moved across country. Unfortunately it has taken me longer to adjust to being with other people.

I was born approximately December 25, 2016

I am approximately 19 pounds, I love walks and could stand to lose a few pounds but who couldn't!

I am standoffish at first but do warm up to my person and love to sit with you, receive love, snuggle under the blanket.

My Adoption fee includes, I have been fixed, up to date on core vaccines (5 in 1, bordetella & rabies), dewormed and microchipped.

If Interested PLEASE contact PATCH Rescue Inc. patchrescue@gmail.com or (760) 706-0728

Adopt a Pet Listings =

https://www.adoptapet.com/adoption_rescue/93645-patch-rescue-inc-victorville-california

PetFinder Listings =

https://www.petfinder.com/member/us/ca/victorville/patch-rescue-inc-ca2487/

Adoption process is verbal interview to determine if we think your family is the right situation for the fur kid you are interested in, application (can be downloaded here: https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/0B9ZDmKaRLnYfbDZLbDN5Y3hYeWM?usp=sharing), once application is reviewed and approved home check will be performed. Then we say you are becoming part of the PATCH family adopting one of our fur kids, so we expect follow up on our family member throughout their life, i.e. text, email, social media, pictures are our favorite for sharing with the PATCH family!

Please keep in mind we are 100% volunteer run We do not have a facility, completely foster based, so we all have our real jobs, it could take 24 to 48 hours to receive a response.

Thank you for considering adoption to save two lives!

DURING THE COVID 19 SHUT DOWN, WE WILL BE HOLDING ADOPTIONS BY APPOINTMENTS ONLY.   We will return to CAL Ranch once deemed safe for the public and our volunteers to do so.  

Pongo is about  3  yrs old and weighs about 40  lbs.  He does not like other animals so needs a home where he is king of his castle.  He needs a house with a secure yard, so he can play and pottie in peace without other having to defend his honor.    

He needs a home with teenagers, no small children (he has never been around them)  He is housebroken and trained.   His previous owner lived in an apartment and could not keep him.  More will be known about me soon.   

A Path 4 Paws holds adoption events EVERY Saturday & Sunday from 10am-4pm at C-A-L Ranch,  located at 232 N. Jones Blvd right off the I-95.   Please bring your dog(s) for a meet and greet (if applicable)  Please bring your entire family so everyone can meet. 

If you are interested in Pongo, please contact dogrescuelv@hotmail.com to confirm the dog you are interested in,  will be attending that particular weekend.  We have limited space at the store, therefore we can not take every dog out to the event.

Pongo is spayed/neutered, has current vaccinations and includes a microchip, deworming and 2 free vet visits.  Adoption fee applies.  Please make sure you have read the information listed on the homepage for requirements and restrictions. 

Foster homes & volunteers are always needed.  Please contact us regarding how you can help by fostering or volunteering for our organization.

animal.description:
Mr. Darcy was picked up wandering the streets and brought into a vet clinic. No owner claimed him and the vet couldn't keep him and asked if I would help. He was in pretty rough shape. But after much vetting he is all healthy now and is a handsome little gentleman. He is super sweet and low maintenance and perfect in the house. He is blind with cataracts in both eyes. But he gets around fine. He is well tempered and gets along with everyone. I wish that all the minpins were as happy and easy going as him.

If you are interested in adopting, please cut and paste the link below to fill out an adoption application:

https://form.jotform.com/92916416469165

After the application is processed and approved, a home visit and meet and greet with the dogs will be scheduled. If there are any fencing issues, make sure that repairs are done prior to the home visit. MinPins are natural escape artists! Typically, the adoption is finalized the day after the home visit and meet and greet. Out of area adopters would need to drive/fly in to meet the dogs and adopt.

animal.description:
Who wants to adopt a whacky wierdo? HAHA! Belle is a Husky/Herding breed mix who we placed as a puppy. She was returned due to the owner having an illness and could no longer care for her. She has since been placed twice and returned for biting.  Belle has been in her current foster home for about a year and has had zero nipping but she does have some minor issues. Belle is cage aggressive. She is a dog where everything as to be on her terms. She is fearful and panicky when forced to do anything. We will only place her in a dog savvy home that knows how to work with a quirky canine. She seems to show her weirdness when in a new home. Belle is housebroken, vaccinated, spayed, and microchipped. She does not like cats but is very playful with other dogs. Belle is crate trained and would do best with a fenced yard. Belle recently had acl surgery so hiking and a super active family will not work for her. No kids and no cats.

Donations can be available for immediate use if sent to Northeast PA Pet Fund and Rescue via PayPal nepapetfund@gmail.com 

All adoption fees go towards getting the dog up-to-date on all shots, bordetella, spay/neuter, micro-chip, and all vet visits to get them healthy!

Please text 570-357-8032 for more info or fill out an application on https://nepapetrescue.com/

animal.description: My name is Egor (DOB 2012). Egor is a special boy with special needs.  He is looking for a forever person who is highly experienced and willing to train & work with him.  Egor had a difficult life before being rescued, we don't know what happened to him, however, he is fearful of people and aggressively protects his space.  Egor was at a high kill shelter when FCSR stepped in to save him.  He was heartworm positive and has been treated for it.  Now, Egor has developed a full cataract in one eye and the other eye is getting cloudy.  He will need to be the only dog.  Egor has a lot of trust issues with people and must be handled at his own pace.  When put in a crate, Egor needs to be left on a leash in order to get him out. If you have experience with Egor's type of behaviors & personality and would like to help him, please complete your application at www.floridacocker.org. For more details, call 813-245-1833 or contact info@floridacocker.org.

animal.description:
Sweet Sunny (DOB June 4, 2011) was turned in because his family couldn't take care of his skin. He is a sweet, quiet boy with really bad skin allergies. He requires an injection once a month from the vet called Cytopoint for environmental allergies ($90), prescription dry-eye drops once or twice a day called Tacrolimus ($60 a bottle) and a prescription anti-itch pill called Apoquel once a day ($59). Then, at intervals, he needs a course of antibiotics and anti-fungal pills for breakthrough skin infections for 3 to 6 weeks at a time. And, of course, as a cocker posatex ear cream for the occasional ear infection. We are looking for a home that has a strong vet history we can confirm and the means and ability to provide this care to Sunny. 
Please complete your application at www.floridacocker.org. For more details, call 813-245-1833 or contact info@floridacocker.org.

animal.description:
To access the home page for our group, click on Southern Comfort Maltese Rescue which will take you to the map page.  Below the map is our logo and the link to click on to access adoption forms, contact info or to donate. ALL DONATIONS ARE TAX DEDUCTIBLE.


Adoption Fee:  $175.00

Zoey Grace is a very sweet but a scared little girl.  She is 12 years old and weighs 9.11 pounds. 
 
Zoey Grace is painfully shy, frightened and scares easily, so because of her actions, we believe she has gone thru some sort of trauma both physically and mentally.  Anyone adopting Zoey Grace will have to be patient with her and be willing to give her time to adjust, even if it means months of love and care, if not years.  She has been in rescue for 2 years and is still trying to learn to trust.  Her veterinarian described her as being "scared of the world".
 
Zoey is not house trained and is the reason why she was surrendered. She was not able to be house trained,and she will pee in the bed and also in her doggie bed..  She may need to wear diapers (she does not currently wear them so she may not want to), depending on how a new pet parent will be with her lack of house manners, and she eats her poop, called Coprophagia. There is no cure for this habit.  There are a lot of "home remedies" that people will suggest but none really work. 

She does not walk on a leash,and will hug the ground and is considered a flight risk, so we will require that there be a secure fenced yard for her safety.

Because of her extreme behavior of being scared, SCMR will require applicants to have a veterinarian reference that will be able to confirm that she will be well cared for and loved for who she is.
 
Also, she is an alpha dog. She gets along with some dogs but will fight and dominate female dogs.  There are no cats in the foster home so it is unknown how she would be around them

Please know that Zoey Grace is doing well. She is loved and well cared for in her foster home and is happy in Gainesville, FL


NOTE: SCMR DOES NOT adopt to homes with children under the age of 10 years or homes with Electric Fences

Out-of-state adoptions are possible; however, the approved adoptive home is responsible for making the necessary arrangements to pick up their new little one.
animal.name: Zoey Grace (FL)
