animal.description: ***Application must be filled out to meet or adopt Nico*** Nico is a 6 year old male dachshund mix who was originally adopted from Revolution Rescue in July 2016. He was returned to rescue December 27th, 2017 after he became paralyzed and was diagnosed with Intervertebral Disc Disease (IVDD). Nico weighs 18 pounds and is a happy little guy who is loving life and isn’t phased by the fact he can’t walk. He is currently receiving chiropratic and acupuncture treatments and taking a couple herbal supplements for his IVDD. He loves going for car rides and taking walks in the neighborhood in his set of wheels which will go with him when he is adopted.  He prefers not to use the wheels at home as he can get around very well without them. Nico can stand and has taken a few steps on his own! His foster mom expresses his bladder a few times a day. Don’t let this scare you as it’s very easy to learn and Nico doesn’t mind it at all. He does wear a belly band when he’s scooting around the house to help with accidents. Nico gets along with most dogs and cats but will chase a cat if they run as he thinks they are playing. He enjoys playing with other dogs and is constantly trying to get his foster fur siblings to play with him. He can be a little stubborn and slow to trust, but he loves to be with his foster mom, shower her with kisses, and follow her everywhere. Nico is looking for a patient, loving family that will continue with his treatment plan and love him regardless if he’s able to walk again. He is current on vaccinations, neutered, and microchipped. His adoption fee is $225.00. If you are interested in adopting Nico please visit our website at www.revolutionrescue.com and complete an application and someone will be in touch.

Rover's match making procedure is to complete the application after which a telephone interview will be conducted along with your reference checks. At that time, if appropriate, a home visit will be scheduled for the dog to come to your home and meet you.

At Rover’s Rest Stop it’s …all about the Dog ! We love our kids and want the best forever placement with the easiest transition to their new home. To that end, they are with us approximately two to six months or longer, which is individual to each kid, to achieve optimum health, rehabilitation, and training.

Pet name:   Stitch – LA

Breed(s): Bull Dog mix
Color: White 
Gender: Male
Est. Age: 3 - 4 yrs 
Est. Weight: 50 - 55 pounds 
Energy Level: High, active 

Apartment:  No 
House trained: Yes
Crate trained: Yes
Microchipped: Yes
Spay / Neutered: Yes
Current vaccinations: Yes
Training: Basic Obedience
Dog-friendly: Yes
Cat-friendly: Yes 
Kid-friendly: Yes

Stitch is such a great guy! He is very friendly with children and people. Stitch does well with most female dogs and some male dogs. He is active and loves to play all day. He needs to be in an air conditioning, indoor environment because he is light & heat sensitive. Stitch has one incurable flaw, non-stops barking. Barks at any noise, movement, and then barks at the barking. He is not suitable for an apartment and needs a home with enough distance to the neighbors not to bother them with barking.  

Please help us find this wonderful dog a forever home with their own family.

Adoption donation fee and home inspection required.
Application for adopting and fostering - https://form.jotform.com/201328449376157

Thank you,

animal.description:
This is Percy (HWTH#18138A). She is a German Shepherd mix, DOB: 7/9/17. Percy weighs 47 pounds and stands 21 inches at the shoulders now with just a little more growing and some filling out to do. Her previous owners got her as a small pup, they live in a mobile home park and Percy has out-grown the space they have for her. She is also a really high-energy girl who needs room to run and an active owner willing to give her the love, good-quality human companionship, playtime, exercise and training necessary for Percy to reach her full potential. Percy is a beautiful girl, very loving and is searching for her pack leader. She could be a good running companion, hiking dog, possibly a good dog to get involved in a dog sport - anything that will gives her exercise, your companionship and gives her a purpose. When Percy is thoroughly settled in her new Forever home, she will benefit from positive basic obedience training to help with leash training and the bonding process. Once Percy has bonded with her new owner, she will make a most loyal canine companion. She is crate trained. For more information on Percy, please call Sandy at tele # 661-824-4495 (this is a land-line phone).

Percy doesn't come to Petco or A Better Way Pet Care. She can be seen at the rescue by calling Suzanne Poth at 661-824-4393 to make arrangements.

Percy does not do well with other animals and requires a very experienced handler.
We believe Percy would be best in a home with no kids under the age of 10 years.

I am about three years old, so have a lot of life ahead! I hope it is with you!

animal.description:
Felix is a 4 year old, 15 pound tan beagle mix. He is one of a large group of similar dogs we got together who were not socialized to people. All are shy, but most haven't been aggressive. Most have now been adopted- just Felix and Shirley Bassey are left.
Felix is now to a point where he seems to about to have a breakthrough in overcoming his shyness. He loves other dogs, even big ones. He used to be great playmates with a big hound we had. He has gotten to be comfortable at taking treats out of volunteers' hands, and he is also good at going in and out of his kennel for exercise time. One volunteer was even able to get him to walk on a leash a little.
He will still need a home that is patient with him. His people will have to make sure he can't run out the front door or escape the yard.
Neutered, has a chip, and all his shots.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

animal.description:
Wookie is a big, quiet senior red who is very soulful, and likes human company more than being a part of the pack. He prefers to hang by himself and loves to be around his special people. Wookie has a strong voice that sounds bigger than he is. Although he will occasionally play a little with other dogs at his Foster Home, he is generally a little picky about most dogs and does not like to share. He is not cat friendly and isn't really a fan of smaller dogs. Wookie isn't high on energy but will play with a tennis ball and LOVES stuffed animals to tear apart and carry around - Wookie also loves to watch TV and hang with the family for quiet snuggling on the couch or spend time hanging outside on a patio. Wookie loves car rides but will need help if he needs to jump up into a higher vehicle.

Originally it was reported that Wookie was deaf, this is unlikely, we think he just had a strong case of husky selective hearing!

animal.description:
If you're looking for a loyal, smart, fun-loving four-legged friend, Blue should definitely be at the top of your list. This handsome boy is so full of love and he's eager to share it. I believe that Blue is convinced he's a teeny, tiny lap dog. When he wants attention he's not pushy, he simply puts his head on your shoulder or in your lap, sometimes he'll put his paw on your leg.
Blue's a very smart dog and the expression on his face when being talked to leads me to believe he understands what I'm saying. Once proper introductions are made he's very good with other dogs. He is kind of a silly klutz, known to run right into the wall or trip easily over himself. I feel he will flourish in a home where he has a lot of space with a backyard. He's good-natured and obedient, does great at the dog park and walks well on a leash. Blue complies to all basic commands...sit, stay, stop, come, no. When his kennel is available he'll relax inside it but he doesn't have to be confined to a kennel, he's fully potty trained as long as he's taken out. Has he has a strong curiosity toward cats but doesn't show any signs of aggression or violence. Blue doesn't bark a lot. I think he reserves his voice for when strangers approach the house or sometimes he'll bark playfully when he wants attention. He has a lot of energy but is also content sitting with you while you read or watch TV. If you let him he'll snuggle right up with you to go to sleep. Basically he's just a big ole friendly lug who offers a lifetime of devotion, friendship and love.

Hello! I bet you're wondering how I got my name? When I was a stray I would jump over a 4-foot fence to play with a female Pit Bull, so people started calling me her boyfriend. 

I'm friendly with all ages, but due to my size and strength I would do best in a home with children at least 8 years old. As you can tell by my photos my favorite thing is to play with a ball, especially if someone throws it for me! 

I've been living outside, but would love to be an inside pet where I can be a constant, loving companion. Did you know that dogs who have lived outdoors are easily house trained, because we know that is where we do our business? 

If you would like to meet me in person please contact Giles County Humane by calling or sending them an email. 
(rcw)

animal.description:
Name: Groot
 
Approximate Age: 1 1/2yrs (Nov 2016) 

Breed: Pit mix 

Sex: Male 

Special Needs: Deaf 

Adoption fee: $325.00 

Up to date on vaccinations/preventatives, neutered, microchipped

I few months ago, I was with a different rescue but because of my deafness, SNARR took me in. I'm new to this learning sign language and what my teachers are trying to get from me but give me time- i'm going to figure it out!
I'm a rather large boy, just shy of 75lbs...and I have been known to forget how big I am when i'm playing with other animals. At my foster home, there's a few horses that i'm no longer to hang out with since I keep nipping their legs to try to get them to pay attention to me. Other dogs, I have been known to be rather rambunctious with so a home with a dog that can handle that would be best. Also, because of my lack of size knowledge, it is not recommended that I go to a home with cats or any other small animals because I could unintentionally hurt them when all I mean to do is play. I'm just an enormous puppy!
My foster says i'm very sweet & once i trust you, i'm extremely loyal & my goofy personality comes out.
I have gotten a little anxious when my humans leave me alone, but a bone filled with peanut butter usually does the trick at keeping me occupied for awhile. 
For the first week & a half of being in my new foster home I was nervous & would cry whenever I couldn't see her but have since calmed enough that i'm ok for about 4 hours alone or about 6 hours with another dog to keep me company.

*Transport to any approved home within the US is provided at no additional cost. 
Currently Groot is located in Snohomish, Washington

*Please visit SNARRANIMALRESCUE.org to check out our adoption requirements/process and to fill out an application!

animal.description:
Hi.  My name is Katie.  I came to TIRR Rescue from Houston, where I was a street dog.

I lived in a couple of foster homes, but I am an excellent escape artist and it was very hard for my foster and rescue people to catch me.  I became what they call a "flight risk," so I can no longer be left alone in a yard at all.

Because of my time on the streets, I am very distrustful of humans.  I don't so much fear them as just simply not trust them.  I am ok with kids - their words and actions don't conflict like with so many adults.

However, I am slowly learning to trust my rescue people, and my roommate Buccee has helped me gain confidence in humans.

You may complete an application for approval to start the adoption process at www.stanlycountyhumanesociety.org, under the 'Adoption' tab.
Thanks for considering adopting a rescue pet!
Follow us on FaceBook!Adoption fees for pets with Stanly County Humane Society are to cover the following:
*Spay/Neuter

*All standard vaccinations
*Rabies Vaccination
*Microchip

Jasper is a loving, affectionate and calm 12 year old German Shorthaired Pointer. He is very gentle, he loves people, and is great with children. He likes lots of attention, belly rubs and taking naps.  He is quiet and does not bark when inside with people. His dislike is being cooped up inside a kennel when his people leave.  He is housebroken but has a tendency to chew on toys left out by our children.  Jasper does not need lots of space to run outside or very much exercise.  He does well off leash in our yard (no fence)  but is most happy being inside on a soft bed next to me in my office.  He would make a great pet for someone who spends a lot of time at home, wants some ears to scratch and an occasional walk around the block.  

For more information on Jasper please visit www.makrescue.org and fill out an adoption application.
Jasper is located in St. Louis

animal.description: Jango is practically the definition of "overlooked" at FOHA, and his extended tenure at the shelter is truly a mystery to those who know him. Despite how handsome he is, he has been known to not show well in his run, often lowering his head and looking uninvitingly at passersby. This, however, is no indication of his true disposition: Jango is sensitive, playful, well-behaved, and affectionate. He is also a deeply loyal companion who bonds strongly with his family. He can thus be protective, so care should be taken in introducing him to strangers coming into his home. Jango can be selective about the canine company he keeps, but he has gotten along with many dogs when he is properly introduced. Though he's not a puppy anymore, he still has a lot of energy and loves his walks and time chasing toys in the play yard. Smart, attentive, and food-motivated, Jango knows "Sit" and will likely be easily trainable. If you're ready to bestow upon him the time, care, and attention Jango needs, he will reward you with unending loyalty and companionship!Jango would do best in a home with children over 15 and as an only dog.This dog can only be adopted within the Washington DC metro area

He is a very tolerant dog and he does well in playgroup. We don't feel that he is going to do well with small kids, as he is very rough and tumble when he plays and he has no idea that he is about 75lbs. He thinks its fun to run into you while he is playing. Tucker is going to need a patient home with lots of understanding of positive reinforcement training in order to make him feel comfortable. An only dog situation for this kid would be preferred. If you feel that you might be able to provide Tucker with what he is looking for that would be great. Please don't hesitate to contact us. CHS is very committed to our adopters getting the best possible adoption experience that they can. Due to that we ask that prior to arrival at the shelter you please call 503-397-4353 or email animalwelfare@columbiahumane.org to make appropriate arrangements. Most of our dog adoptions are done by appointment only, as we have very limited staff and we want to be able to give ample time to our adopters. They deserve that as well as our dogs deserve it.For more information call 503-397-4353 or email animalwelfare@columbiahumbia.org

LuLu is good with other dogs and cats but would do best in a home with no small children. She's also crate trained.

animal.description:
CALI is a gentle, 4-year-old, 35-pound German Shepherd and Labrador Retriever mix who's lived through a terrible act of heartless cruelty.

In CALI's Own Words:

Let me tell you how it all happened. It all started back in Creek County Oklahoma. My brother Pecos and I were stray dogs, I won't get into how all that came about as I assume you don't have all day. Anyway, we were doing what we could to get by, and I'm not going to lie to you, we were getting into some trouble, and people didn't like it. You know, knocking over trash cans, chasing people's chickens... stuff like that. But then we made a friend! A kind old man who lived all by himself felt sorry for us and started feeding us. He was a really good guy and we loved him. Then one day, we heard a neighbor, a really unpleasant guy, yelling at our friend, "STOP FEEDING THOSE DAMNED DOGS! IF YOU DON'T GET RID OF THOSE DAMNED DOGS I'M GOING TO GET RID OF THEM FOR YOU!" Well, he was being mean to our friend and we didn't like that one bit, so we went over there to see what was going on. But before we knew what happened, that angry man came after us with a piece of pipe! He smashed Pecos across the face with it and then he whacked ME! It really hurt, he broke my face! My jaw was cracked and dislocated, I couldn't move my mouth, and Pecos was even worse, he was bleeding all over the place! We didn't know what else to do but run! If we gave him the chance to hit us again he would have killed us! Before we could even figure out what we were going to do to help our friend, we were being chased by the authorities! Someone must have called them and blamed the whole thing on us! They caught up to us, trapped us, and then threw us in the slammer. It was horrible, we couldn't eat or drink or sleep, it just hurt so bad. Then, something amazing happened. Some really kind people, "The Animal People", got us out of there. All the dogs on the streets and in the pounds talk about The Animal People, but none of them really believe they exist. Well, Pecos and I know... THEY DO! Anyway, they got us all fixed up and brought us to New Jersey so they could find homes for us. And that's my story!

You might be thinking, "Any dog that's been treated that badly would never trust people again." I'll tell you this, nothing could be further from the truth! I think people are Angels and I want one for my very own!

Will you be my beloved person?

Yours,
~ Cali

PLEASE NOTE:  Cali does best with another similar-sized male dog.  CALI is not a friend of cats and cannot be placed in a home with them. She would not do well with small dogs either. 

WHAT'S NEXT?

If you would like to meet, foster, or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY!

Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date!

***

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives.

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs.

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details.

To fill out an adoption application, go to:
https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-BullBreed: Pit Bull Terrier
Gender: Female
Estimated Date of Birth: November 7, 2015
Size: 52 lbs
Location: Stockbridge, GA

RESCUING MOXIE

Moxie, formerly known as Penelope, was surrendered to Henry County Animal Control. She belonged to a military veteran, struggling with his mental health. Moxie is deaf. He had her trained on a shock collar, but he let her off leash and would shock her at a high level until she cried in order to find her location. This poor man who served our country and was unable to take care of himself let alone a dog so Moxie ended up at Animal Control.

ABOUT MOXIE

Due to her deafness, Moxie does startle if she cannot see you coming, however she is extremely loving. Moxie adores people and is getting all the TLC she needs in foster care. She is housebroken and crate-trained. She is an active girl who loves to chase a Kong and play fetch. Sometimes when she runs, she throws both legs back at the same time and looks like a bunny! Although she is deaf, she already knows sit, down, kennel-up, and fetch as she is food-motivated and really wants to make her people happy. She knows how to fetch and doesn't mind people taking the ball away from her. Once she burns off some energy, Moxie is happy to cuddle and is incredibly sweet. Moxie would LOVE a forever family that can show her the joys of being surrounded by love and stability. She needs someone patient and willing to work with her as learning takes longer due to her hearing loss. She might be okay with a calm canine companion her size or larger as well as she occasionally gets to play with two large male dogs at the Pit Bull Palace, although slow introductions are necessary as she can be picky about her dog friends.

Photo Album of Moxie: https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.1843166589074832&type=1&l=37a435a9ac

Our adoption fee is $300. All dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed or neutered, micro-chipped, on heartworm prevention, and are fed top of the line grain-free food.www.savingpitbulls.org

animal.description:
Me, your forever best friend? I would have to be the luckiest dog in the world! I am Ritter! I am an 80 pound, four year old,  sweet boy who loves to cuddle with my people. I love running outside for a little bit every day, so I need a fenced backyard. I am very intelligent, I am crate trained, potty trained and know basic commands. I do well on my leash, I pull a little at the beginning of the walk but I can't help it, I'm excited to hang out with you. I do not want to live with any other dogs. I do well with older, respectful kids. I need a family that will take me for walks in a quiet neighborhood. My favorite things in the world are belly rubs so my only requirements for my forever home are love and belly scratches.  I recently had an issue with my eyes which left me needing them removed so I am getting used to life without sight.  I am adapting very well but need a calm, predictable home and a solid routine in order to flourish.   If you're looking for a buddy who just loves to hang out with you, then I’m your guy!

*I am a graduate of the Pups for Parole training program. I now have all the basic training necessary to make a great companion. I will need a family willing to continue my training, I sure don't want to forget all that I have learned!*

My adoption fee is sponsored and includes my spay/neuter, vaccinations, wellness exam, heartworm test, and microchip! If you're interested in meeting/adopting me, please visit www.rescueonespringfield.com/our-adoption-process/adoption-application/ and fill out the form! We do adopt out of state with vet references and video home check. *Adopter is responsible for coming to get the dog and returning the dog if they adoption does not work out*

animal.description:
Hello.  My name is Brandi.  I have been at TIRR Rescue since 2017.

I came to TIRR Rescue from a breeder, but I never provided puppies to sell.  Perhaps this is why I don't like meeting new people or dogs.  I choose those whom I will trust carefully and do so in my own time.  For a while after I arrived at TIRR Rescue, I didn't spend time with any other dogs.  However, I am better adjusted now and tolerate some of the other dogs here.

I am very protective and territorial.  Once I decide you are my person, I will be completely loyal and trustworthy.  However, though I will be ok with people that I live with, I will never be ok with strangers or "intermittents" (frequent visitors).  I will need to be crated whenever there are visitors, because I can be snappy, and I will bite.

I will need a very unique person (or possibly even a couple) who will understand my unique personality and can handle me.  My adopter will need to be a strong leader.  If you think you are that person, be sure to contact my rescue people!

~~~~

PERSONALITY:
Brandi is a very unique dog with a very unique personality.  She was never socialized and, as such, does not do well with strangers.  She will do best in a home with one person (or perhaps two people) who understand her temperament.  When she decides who her person is, she is very loyal and very protective.  Her adopter will need to understand this and handle her appropriately when other are around.  It is very important that Brandi is set up for success, meaning she is not put in a situation where she will bite; she cannot be allowed around anyone other than the people with whom she lives.

~~~~

To learn more about Brandi, please visit tirrrescue.org/brandi.
animal.name: Brandi

Hello.  My name is Butterfly.  I came to TIRR Rescue with my brother, Ralph, and my sister, Gabby.  We were all mostly feral when we got here and didn't really trust humans.

I am still working on the trusting humans part.  Sometimes, if you reach out to me, I will sniff your hand, but I do not like to be touched just yet.  However, if your back is turned and you are doing something that keeps your attention off me, I will come up behind you and sniff you, push my nose against your legs, and start to get playful.

I am going to need a very structured and quiet home.  My people will have to give me lots of love and have lots of patience, but the time will be rewarded.

Amora was a mommy dog and all of her babies have then since been adopted and now she is patiently waiting for someone to love her as much as we do!

Intake date/origin: August 2015, transfer from an overcrowded shelter
Vetting: Already neutered, microchipped, and UTD on vaccines including rabies
Adoption fee: SPONSORED BY A GENEROUS SUPPORTER
Location: Shelter facility

Meet handsome, independent Diego. This guy is an amazing dog for the right person. What do we mean by amazing? Well, Diego can pretty much take care of himself – he is content just to play by himself and find the comfiest couch to lounge upon. Born in 2014, Diego hasn’t come across the right person yet, but we’re hopeful that there’s someone out there for him.

The right home for Diego consists of one person who wants a dog just to have the company of a four-legged friend. Ideally, this person would let Diego peacefully exist in the home and provide him with a few toys and access to a fenced-in backyard. While Diego does enjoy a back scratch here and there and an occasional “good boy,” he really prefers to be left by himself most of the time. He also does not appreciate being restrained, making it very difficult to put a collar or leash onto him, so this is why he must have a fenced-in yard.

Diego has befriended many other dogs here at the shelter. However, he can be possessive of his food, toys, and anything he claims as his (such as the couch), so he must be the only pet in a home with no children. On the plus side, Diego is completely housetrained, he knows an array of cues, and he is a highly-trainable dog.

Diego has been neutered, vaccinated, and microchipped. If you are interested in adopting Diego, please fill out an adoption application for him at www.lovingheartanimalshelter.org/adopt.

Will you be the person to love Diego and give him a chance at a home?

animal.description:
Ida is part of the Forever Loved Program. The Forever Loved Program is geared toward pets who have medical issues, behavioral issues, or who are older age or hospice cases. Pets in this program will be adopted out as a forever foster. Our program will provide for all medical needs (such as specialty foods, medicine, and/or vetrinary care) for the rest of the pets life. The Forever Loved program is only available to residents of Alabama. ***Ida is part of the forever loved program due to congestive heart failure. Ida is currently on three pills twice a day to help her heart function better and to keep excess fluid from building up in her system. Ida is considered a hospice case due to this.***

All dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are up to date on vaccinations, spayed/neutered (age appropriate), and heartworm negative. All dogs are given monthly flea/tick preventative, monthly heartworm preventative, and are dewormed regularly. Dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are microchipped. Adoption fee is $50. Home visit and vet reference required. Applications can be put in online at http://www.troyanimalrescueproject.org/adopt.php or in person at our rescue center.

The address for our rescue center is 34 County Road 2266, Brundidge, AL 36010. We are one turn off Hwy 167. If you use Google maps, type in Troy Animal Rescue Project and it will take you right to us. Hours of operation are from 10-3 daily. We are open Saturdays and Sundays. No appointment necessary for pets that are located at the rescue center. Appointments must be made to visit pets in foster homes. Location information will be listed beside the pets name if they are at a location other than our rescue center.

Questions can be emailed to troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com or call 334-508-2367.

animal.description:
Tibby is the very sweetest dog in the world. She loves to cuddle and be petted. She is the little ambassador to all the dogs at the rescue. She will go and greet each one everyday in her cart. Despite having only two legs, she would play fetch all day long if she could. She is also our little mermaid, summer time she thinks swimming all day every day is her job. 

Noah's Arks Rescue is all about giving an Abused Animal a second chance at life and to experience what true love is. We take animals that have been tortured, abused, and neglected and supply the emergency medical care required to get them well. We then provide rehab physically and mentally to prepare them for their new home and new life. We are located in Ridgeland, SC., and are by appointment only. All of our dogs are at our Rehabilitation Center either in hospice care or being loved on by staff until we find them forever homes. Please call 843.540.6755 or email NoahsArksRescues@mac.com with any questions. If you are interested, please fill out our Adoption Application at https://www.noahs-arks.net/nar-application. We do adopt out of state and will arrange transports. Our dogs are not allowed to fly cargo at any time.

animal.description:
Hosmer
Alright baseball fans, we know everyone is upset about Eric Hosmer leaving the Royals but we promise that his handsome furry namesake is the best sports fan you could ask for! Hosmer is a 3 year old pit bull mix that was left behind when his owners were evicted. He had a very serious skin infection that has now healed but he does have some allergies that are being managed with the right food and medications. Hosmer is still learning manners but he is working really hard and will do anything for a treat. He is fostered with others dogs and does well, especially with small dogs but he is still learning how to play nice and share. Hosmer will need a home that understands his breed and will be firm but understanding and patient. He is very energetic and is learning how to walk better on a leash but he loves car rides and is a fantastic co-pilot. Hosmer is also very vocal when he plays and when he is expressing his feelings and his foster mom says he is the best cuddle bug when he is tired. He does well with kids but he is still learning how big he is and he is unfortunately allergic to cats! If you are looking for a quirky, energetic furry family member than Hosmer is your guy!

animal.description:
Hi everyone, Shane here! I am looking for a home and the special people in my life told me I needed to introduce myself to you in order to find one. So let me tell you all the things I love. I love people and attention, and I love to play. I like to run around the play yard and occasionally I forget to hit my brakes in time and I run into my human. But I run right over and crawl into their lap to make sure they’re okay! Belly rubs are great, and of course, I really like mealtime! I love to play with other friendly dogs, and I don’t mind sharing my space with a cat. There are a few things I don’t like. I really don’t like fireworks, or thunderstorms - they scare me, and I need my human to comfort me and calm me. And, well, I hate to admit this, but I can get jealous if my human is paying attention to another dog besides me. I guess I can get a bit possessive of my humans, but I’m working on sharing. I also do not like when someone tries to steal my special treasures...finders keepers and all that stuff. I like my humans and friends and really want a home, and a special family all my own. Will you help me with continued work and patience to work through my few challenges? I am a very good, very sweet boy who just needs patience and consistency...and a furever home!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Maybe it's a good thing that 8 1/2-year-old Tracy is almost blind. We wouldn't want her to see how quickly other dogs are being adopted from New Rattitude, while she has waited month after month without a single application. Honestly, we don't get it! This sweet 26-lb. Rattie mix has no other physical problems or any behavioral issues, and caring for her diminishing eyesight requires no medication. All she needs is someone who can work with her limited vision by keeping her environment physically consistent and predictable. She will surprise you with her ability to move about with ease both indoors and out. Needless to say, her adopting family should not have young children, who are rarely consistent or predictable, but she would make a great companion to an older adult who is home most of the time. In fact, she would very much enjoy sitting beside you on the couch and 'watching' TV. Like most other dogs, Tracy does have personal preferences when it comes to living amicably with other furry friends, but those preferences are not unreasonable. She is not a fan of cats, period. In fact, you would think her vision is 20/20 when she stands at the fence and barks at any cat that walks by! Tracy would also rather not have to put up with those quick-to-correct dogs who might take offense to her accidentally bumping into them. (She means no harm; she just didn't see them!) She gets along with more mellow dogs, however. Tracy is house-trained and walks nicely on a leash, so you'll have a live-in partner to help you meet your daily step goal! Truly her needs are very simple--to love and be loved. Tracy's not asking for pity; she's just asking for a chance. Treat yourself to more photos of Tracy at https://imageevent.com/newrattitude/tracy , and then treat yourself to Miss Tracy.
Our adoption fee is $175 for adult dogs or $225 for puppies under 6 months old.

If you are interested in adopting this dog,
PLEASE READ THE DETAILED ADOPTION PROCESS information on our website
at www.
NewRattitude.org/adopt/

From there, you can access our adoption application or contact our Adoption Team for more info.

animal.description:
Magic is a very lucky boy to have escaped death at Animal Control. He joined BAARK’s Rescue & Adoption Program last year, another senior black dog dumped at Chicago Animal Control by an owner who no longer wanted him. So sad that Magic has been with us for so long…another big black dog!

Magic is a very handsome boy,  8-9 years old, about 65 lbs. We are not certain of his breed but he appears to perhaps be a Lab – Shepherd Mix…with those big pointy ears! He’s friendly but cautious, very well-mannered,  an overall low-maintenance kind of guy.  While Magic can co-exist with other dogs, he definitely prefers calm, senior dogs like himself. Magic is said to have previously lived with cats….he may be OK with a senior cat who will not startle him with quick movements.   In addition to napping and sleeping, Magic loves long walks and car rides…he walks nicely on a leash but at a quick pace and he’s a GREAT passenger!! Magic would be very stressed by dog parks, doggy day care, or over-active children. 

In spite of his neglectful past, Magic is a well-balanced, personable boy who most definitely deserves a wonderful home of his own. He’s just looking for a quiet peaceful place to spend his twilight years, and have a family of his own to care for him and share his life. An adult home is preferred. No children under the age of 12 years.

Like all of BAARK’s dogs, Magic is fully vetted, neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations, heartworm tested and on year-round heartworm preventative, and microchipped. Magic is in excellent overall health.

If you are interested in adding Magic to your family, or have any questions about him, please contact BAARKDogRescue@gmail.com or 847-852-0895.

Hello humans, I am Zeus. You probably know me as the sky and thunder god in Greek history. But don’t let that scare you, I’m actually a big 120+ lb lover (don’t tell anyone). There is nothing I would like more than to have a family of my own! I’m really smart and know my basic commands and I’m learning to walk on a leash. I have lots of energy and outdoor running games are my favorite, but only outdoors. My foster mom says I have good indoor manners and will stay right by your chair with you...and if you want to pet me the whole time you are sitting there, that’s pyrfect! Don’t get me wrong though, I’m not lazy. I’m always alert. Visitors are fun and I greet them at the door with big tail wags! Food...food - I love my meals! If you can add a little something to my chow I am the happiest. And roast beef treats — YUM, they’re the best! I don’t have any desire to climb or escape. I’m an adult and I know what’s good for me. I just want you to look into my soulful eyes and hug me and kiss me on the top of my head and love me. I am good with children but need to be the only dog so I can get all the attention. All I want is a furever family to protect and love back.

animal.description:
Didi is our latest "Cinderella" transformation. This PB Pyr girl and her pups were surrendered by a farmer who was not pleased that she jumped their little fence and mated with the neighbor's Anatolian Shepherd. Left outside, she was matted, emaciated and had wounds infested with maggots, and even the puppies had maggots attached as well. Didi has been sweet and thankful to be inside and cleaned up, and now she's become a beauty. Now that her pups have been adopted and she's been spayed and back to good health, she's ready for a furever home of her own. After her initial neglect, Didi takes time to warm up to new people, but once she does, she's a sweetie. She is a snuggle-bunny with people, is fine with cats, but can be defensive around other large dogs, so Didi will be placed as an only dog.

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY.  View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
UPDATE:5/2019 Violet is about 1.5yrs old. Violet recently went on a foster to adopt situation and it did not work out because she was very territorial of the foster mom. Violet did great playing with the kids and the husband but if someone wanted to sit next to foster mom Violet wouold growl.  Violet might be best if she were adopted to a single woman. 

UPdate: 9/25/18  Violet is now 9 months old. She is easy going and laid back still but is coming into her guardian instincts and is very loyal to her foster and the property. Violet is still very playful with the other dogs at the rescue and has excellent off leash recall. She is livestock friendly but cat curious. 

Violet is potty trained, leash trained, crate trained and still working on her basic obedience and socializing. 

We were told that she was  st bernard mix when we pulled her from the shelter she was in but as she grows we have our doubts and think she may be great dane mix. She stands about an inch shorter than a 5 yr old German Shepherd and is almost as long as he is and she has about 1 yr and 3 months still to grow. She is going to be a huge girl but she is going to be the most loyal, gentle giant companion to whoever is lucky enough to give her a furever home!! 


4/18Violet is 6months old. She's easy going and laid back but will get in the mix with the other dogs and play! She prefers to be with her humans just leisurely hanging out but she's always up for an adventure!

Do you like to take walks??? Well, this guy is the perfect companion for you! He walks very well on leash and truly enjoys his strolls! This handsome fellow also loves to play and have fun! Baxter enjoys lots of cuddle time and adores being petted and loved. He is house trained and knows his basic commands.

Upon first introduction, Baxter may be shy. He needs a moment to learn that you are a friend. He has been patiently waiting for his forever person or family to take him home. He wants what every pup wants: a safe home where he will be loved. This handsome guy loves his people so much that he can be protective of them as well as his home.

He would do very well in a peaceful, quiet, dog savvy adults only household. He really is a nice little guy who needs a patient and kind family.

Baxter is a 9 1/2 year old German Shepherd mix who is neutered, microchipped, heart worm free and up to date on all vaccines. He is currently at our Freeport location.  

If you would like to meet Baxter or would be interested in fostering him, please download our adoption application and email it to adopt@bobbicares.org, or call our office at 516-378-4340 and speak to Elyse. It would do Baxter a world of good to be in a home of his own. He once lived in a home and was surrendered by his owner who could no longer care for him. Kindly keep in mind that our adoptions are local only (Long Island, Queens, Brooklyn, Manhattan).

RESCUING RIBLETT
Riblett, formerly known as Kate, was picked up as a stray and taken to Gwinnett County Animal Services. She had been hit by a car so on top of being emaciated at merely 20 lbs and filled with worms, she also had a badly fractured hip. We had a foster home open up for a young female puppy so when GCAS reached out to us for help, we just so happened to have the perfect foster home for this little girl. Riblett got her freedom ride and we rushed her over to our vet at New Hope Animal Hospital. After Ribletts pelvis healed, she had FHO surgery on her hip to remove the ball of her femur and allow her to heal more quickly and have less pain. She also had a TPLO on her knee.
ABOUT RIBLETT
Riblett, whom we affectionately call Roo, is a funny girl that likes to play catch me until she sees you have treats, then she comes running and sits at your feet. She loves to run and play, but she is also especially sweet and loving. Riblett needs to be the only pet in the home, but she would make the most adorable and incredible solo companion. She loves her people and has been waiting a long time for a forever family to scoop her up and make her life complete!

Video Playlist of Riblett: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLYDnJXruR1h1-L2AkKYdIwwCcSW0D-rqS

animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-BullBreed: Pit Bull Terrier Gender: Male Estimated Date of Birth: August 18, 2015 Size: 65 lbs Location: Dallas, GA
RESCUING JIGSAW
Jigsaw was seized in a cruelty case in Macon-Bibb County. He weighed 26.8lbs on August 17th, 2017. Our vet said he should weigh a minimum of 45 to 50lbs. His body condition score was a 1 out of 9, one being the worst. He has some badly infected wounds and pressure sores that have ruptured to the bone. His actual hip bones have begun to pop through his skin. On top of being unbelievably thin, Jigsaw has hookworms, coccidia, and he is heartworm positive. He has lived his life on a chain and has developed some behavioral issues. His teeth are worn down to nubs from years of living on a chain and biting at rocks, usually out of frustration.
ABOUT JIGSAW
Although Jigsaw is a game bred pit bull and has lived his life on a chain, Jigsaw is sweet and happy to be around people. In true game dog fashion, he is extremely resilient and despite his condition, he is strong and still wagging his tail for everyone he meets. We were able to get Jigsaw to a healthy weight and has since been fully vetted. Unfortunately, due to his background, Jigsaw has some behavioral nuances that will make him difficult to place. Jigsaw is a silly, unique boy and he loves people, however he will grab hold of any object within reach and will not let go. For this reason, Jigsaw cannot have toys. He will grab a hose, or a broom, or a towel, and getting it back is a struggle. He is currently walked on a chain leash to avoid having to retrieve the leash out of his jaws. For obvious reasons, he is not a fan of other dogs, but he adores people. This boy had a hard start to life and we are giving him the best life we can while he is with us. He currently lives at the Pitbull Palace and it will take a very special family to adopt this boy. If you think you can give Jigsaw the love he so desperately wants and deserves, please contact us!

RESCUING SARAH
Sarah was seized in a dog fighting investigation in Macon-Bibb county. She had been at the shelter for 9 months and she was starting to lose weight. Sarah became urgent and needed to get out of there. Sarahs owner went to jail on animal cruelty charges. Her lip is ripped off. Her face and ears are completely scarred. Her front paw is disfigured and she has some serious wounds to her inner leg. She has been bred multiple times and she was heartworm positive. This poor girl has been through it all.
ABOUT SARAH
Even though Sarah has scars and is missing part of her lip, despite everything she has been through at the hands of humans, she still love everyone she meets. She is resilient and smart and she adores people. She turns into a pile of excited wiggles and happiness when people are around. She loves to run in the yard and will get crazy zoomies. She thinks bones and toys are fun, but she flinches and gets a bit scared if you raise your arm up to throw them for her. She loves food and already knows how to sit and kennel-up, although her missing lip causes her to be a little sloppy when chewing treats. Despite her scars and lack of lip, Sarah is a beautiful dog whose silly personality shines. Sarah would love a family that is kind and enjoys watching her zoom around the yard. She likes to be active, but is also sweet and calm when its time. She would likely do well with older children as she tends to startle at loud noises, like clapping hands. Due to her past, Sarah needs to be the only pet in the home.

RESCUING HOLLY
Holly was found on the side of the road in horrible condition on 12/21/2013. She was extremely skittish and our friend Shawn & his wife spent an hour trying to get her in the car. Shawn thought she had been shot in the chest due to an infection in her mammary. Our vet determined that she had mastitis. On top of the mastitis, Holly was infested with worms and was heartworm positive. She has recovered from her mastitis and underwent heartworm treatment. Holly is now fully-vetted and ready for a forever home.
ABOUT HOLLY
Holly is an extremely loving girl. She is very untrusting of strangers. It takes her a while to warm up to new people, but her love is endless once you have earned her trust. She has been great with the other dogs in her foster home. Holly is crate-trained and housebroken. Due to her weariness of strangers, she can be protective of her home and people. It takes a while to build that trust, but once you have it, Holly will show you how incredibly amazing she really is. Holly needs a family who will be patient, allowing her to warm up and then provide endless belly-rubs! Belly-rubs are this girls thing. She will run as fast as she can and jump onto the couch head first, squirming around, rubbing her face into the couch, only to roll over and demand belly rubs.

animal.description:

Adopt-a-BullBreed: Great Dane/American Bulldog Gender: Male Estimated Date of Birth: April 15, 2012 Size: 85lbs Location: Dallas, GA
RESCUING STONE
Stone was originally adopted from Douglas County Animal Control when he was a small pup. That family gave him to another family, who then gave him to a third family, and he ended up a Fulton County Animal Control. He was next in line to get put to sleep at the shelter and we were able to pull him on the day he was scheduled to be euthanized.
ABOUT STONE
Stone is a giant. Our best guess is that he's a Great Dane/American Bulldog mix. He is a big, playful goof and he loves toys although he has not quite learned to bring them back to you. Stone does not understand his size or strength. It is very clear that a lack of basic obedience and being dumped several times in his formative years has affected him immensely. Stone is not very trusting of new people. He takes time to warm up and can be rather intimidating due to his size and behavior. He is reactive when in public to people and other dogs. Once he trusts you, you are part of his inner circle and he will show you his true personality. His true personality shines he is fun loving, sweet, and silly. Because his previous owners simply dumped him off onto the next family, he lacked all leadership and guidance in his formative years so he does not know what behavior is acceptable and what is not. Stone does jump up on people and could benefit from some serious obedience training. He is reactive on leash in public and will require a strong owner. Stone also has trust issues and insecurities with strangers due to his previous life experiences. He will require a 6 foot privacy fence and a strong, experienced owner that is willing to take the time to get to know him and work with him on obedience. Due to his size and behavioral concerns, we do not recommend Stone for a home with children.

animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-Bull*APPLY TO FOSTER*Breed: Pit Bull Terrier Gender: Male Estimated Date of Birth: March 14, 2013 Size: 58 lbs Location: Dallas, GA
RESCUING ZETH
Zeth came into Fulton County very sick and became one of their longest residents even though he was a shelter favorite and was hanging in the office with the girls. Zeth ended up on the euthanasia list and our good friend at Fulton put out a plea for him. She said Zeth has more personality than any dog she has ever met and she could not let him die in the shelter.
ABOUT ZETH
The shelter workers love to sing Zeths praises. Zeth is a complete character. His eyeliner is always on point. His head is way too large for his body. He enjoys stuffed animals and long trips to Petsmart. Zeth has never met a stranger. He is a pretty typical dog, and prefers to select his canine companions himself rather than be told whom he is required to tolerate. Throughout his stay at Fulton County, he made all the girls laugh with his RZF, Resting Zeth Face, and his silly antics. Zeth has a big head and an even bigger personality. The only thing Zeth truly hates is carrots. He does not care for watermelon, but peanut butter is yummy and cheese is his all-time favorite. He is great at taking treats gently.
Zeth is very smart and wants to please his people. He will do anything for food, but is not that into toys. He already knows sit, no, outside, his name, and he is working on his leash manners as he tends to zig-zag a bit and pull at times. Zeth loves car-rides and will politely ride where ever you put him, quietly window watching until he gets sleepy, then he will lay down. He enjoys snuggling with his people and prefers to rest his head on you. If he's not snuggling, he is watching his humans in the house or chewing a bone. He is not much of a barker, but he can be incredibly silly like when he carries his food or water bowl around. Zeth loves affection and adores a good butt-scratch or ear rub. He is not a fan of baths or his crate, but we are working on acclimating him to both. He is house-trained and does not seem to be destructive in any way.
Zeth would prefer to be an only dog, however we think he may be okay with another submissive dog with a proper introduction. What Zeth wants the most is to be with his people. He loves all people of all shapes, sizes, appearances, and ages. Zeth would love an active family that will shower him with the love and affection he deserves.
*Zeth is in need of a foster home - apply to foster today!*

RESCUING STUBBS
We first met Stubbs when he was 7 weeks old. He was brought to us for help as they thought his leg was broken. Stubbs was not one of our dogs, but we helped the Good Samaritan out by having our vet examine him. It turns out that Stubbs was born without an elbow. He has a deformed front leg that looks like a chicken wing and is not usable. His new 4-legged brother was not fond of him and we took him in as a Forlorn dog.

He may suffer some arthritis in his other shoulder later in life due to having to keep his weight on that one leg. Our vet determined that there was no reason to remove his leg since it doesn't bother him. Stubbs is a goofy boy. Stubbs can be untrusting of new men, but he loves human affection and he has done well with all the dogs that he has met at the Pit Bull Palace.

animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-BullBreed: Pit Bull Terrier Gender: Male Estimated Date of Birth: August 31, 2016 Size: 41 lbs Location: Dallas, GA
RESCUING FABIO
Fabio came from a cruelty case, but we were able to take him into our program and get him healthy. He was packed with intestinal parasites and coccidia, but he has made a full recovery and only his scars remain.
ABOUT FABIO
Fabio is a black pit bull with many, many scars. Jason lovingly named him Fabio because although most would look at him and be frightened (or maybe even not notice him at all), Fabio is a handsome boy to us. Fabio is a small guy, weighing in at about 40 lbs. One would think he would love the comfort of an Air Conditioned home after living outside for so long, but this couch potato of a guy really enjoys sunning on the porch or in the yard. (Seriously, the sun is his favorite!) He is a laid-back, chill guy that will get excited zoomies at feeding time, but afterwards he will curl up on his bed to lounge or nap. He is also good in the tub for bath time and will occasionally chew on a Nylabone to keep him self occupied. He has not been destructive in his foster home. Fabio has a hole in his palate that we tried to have surgically repaired to no avail. Because of this, he eats soft food. Although hard food may irritate the soft tissue of his palate, Fabio is perfectly content eating soft food, he has never been bothered by this odd, genetic malformity, and we don't expect it to cause him any issue in the future.
When he first came to us, Fabio was a little disconnected with people, but he has since fallen head over heels for any kind of human affection. If you spend any time with him, it is instantly obvious that his affection for people is astronomical. He has high desire to please and, in true pittie fashion, he is very emotionally connected now. He loves having visitors and gets excited to meet new people. Although Fabio has exponential love for all people, he needs to be the only pet in the home. He is happiest when snuggled up with you (he's a VERY good snuggler) and he can be a little eager about bed-time. In the late evening, he will tell you it's bed time. He is not a big barker so the only time you'll typically hear him make noise is during feeding time or when he's telling you it's bed time. Due to his unfortunate start in life, being in public and seeing other dogs can stress him out so he would love a family that likes to spend time with him at home. Fabio is ready to crawl into your lap, give you cute little kisses, and steal your heart!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Personality:
We have sweet Mitchell listed as special needs only because he needs socialization. He's an awesome dog but he's skittish and hesitant with people. He needs a home that can and will socialize him and get him out and about to experience life. Mitchell will prefer a quieter home possibly by himself or with another canine friend to play with. He does great with other dogs but doesn't seem to understand or know how to play with others...human and canine alike. He will need time to open up and trust because it doesn't appear that he's had that prior to SSR. He's a very sweet boy that lurks in the background in his foster home but you can see that he wants to be part of the pack. Are you active in hiking, walks and exploring new territory, running a few miles a day? Why not consider Mitchell as a partner for all the above. I'm sure he wants to do it, he just needs a friend to do it with.

None of our foster dogs are tested with cats because we have no way of testing them with cats. Siberians are notorious for their high prey drive and typically kill cats, rabbits, chickens, birds, squirrels, opossums, etc., so we we don't have much success adopting them out to homes with cats. Most of our foster dogs are with us for killing cats, chickens and goats to begin with so our assumption is they are not good with cats and other small things that move.

Siberians are typically good with children of all ages and the only reason we would not list them as not good with kids is because they may be too energetic and bouncy and knock over a toddler.

Southern Siberian Rescue is a volunteer based 501(c)3 organization based out of Raleigh, NC, so we do not have a physical facility with operating hours that you can visit to meet our dogs. All of our foster dogs are in our personal homes. You need to fill out our adoption application (http://www.southernsiberian.com/info/adoption) and get approved to adopt and then we will set a time for you to meet our foster dogs. As a volunteer based group, we all have jobs, family, personal dogs and other commitments but we try to acknowledge and process applications as quickly as we can. That being said, we try to keep our available foster dogs as current as we can also but it is time consuming to get pics and information on new dogs so not all of our dogs are listed at all times. Please fill out our application and then we can discuss dogs that will work for you and your situation. We average 40-45 Siberians in our program so we are certain we have one that will work for you. Please know that we are not obligated to answer inquiries on dogs as we will focus on approved applicants. Again, there is ample time to discuss all of our foster dogs AFTER we have an approved application on file. We do adopt out of state as long as we can get a home check done. We ask that you, your family and existing pets make the trip to NC to meet and adopt our foster dogs.

SSR can not and will not hold dogs for anyone. If we do, that means another Siberian will die in a shelter because a shelter dogs time is very limited, as is our foster space. We do our best to process applications in the order received and first application gets first interest in our foster dog(s). We understand that there will be scheduling conflicts with home checks and meet and greets but we will try to accommodate for that if a potential adopter has interest in a particular foster dog in our program.

All Southern Siberian Rescue foster dogs are microchipped, up to date on shots, spay/neutered, on monthly heartworm preventative and flea and tick preventative. For additional information on Southern Siberian Rescue and Siberian Huskies, please visit www.SouthernSiberian.com. To fill out an application, please visit

http://www.southernsiberian.com/info/adoption
.

Thank you for your inquiry. Tom has been adopted but we have to wait for them to go pick him up after the stay at home is lifted.  Once he is picked up we will remove his profile. Please do not write to us for an application. Sorry for any inconvenience. 











Tom is such a handsome fellow, pictures don't do him justice,  and super nice too.  This guy is about 4 years old and could stand to lose a few pounds. It’s so cute to see him running around with the other dogs in his foster home. He is learning that attention is a very good thing. With kindness and love, he is coming out of his shell at his foster home.

Tom is a sweet and good-hearted guy but he is very shy when you meet him and takes time to warm up. He prefers to sit and hang out rather than crawl onto your lap.  The poor little guy has some trust issues but we are confident that with human kindness he will continue to blossom. Tom gets along great with his foster family's dogs. He will get along fine with cats.

He does need some help with basic commands and going on a diet, but he is a smart little guy and could pick up the basics more if someone will work with him. This doll would be a great addition to a family or individual looking for a wallflower to join their family. He would do ok with no other dog in the house as long as someone was around during the day but finds more courage with another dog around and would prefer a canine companion. Tom would not be happy being alone all day if his people worked a full workday.

Tom’s adoption fee is $275.00 and he is being fostered in San Jose, CA

All our dogs are in private foster homes and arrangements to meet our dogs occur after an application has been received.

If you would like to know more about this sweet boy or receive an application to adopt, please contact us at Dogzonerescue@yahoo.com.

Apply at: http://www.plannedpethood.org/adopt/available-dogs.html

Hi, I’m Eddie. I’m a 4 year old Jack Russell/Pembroke corgi mix. I’m a little guy with no tail and I like to remind the other dogs here in my foster home that they have one. So I’m always biting their tails and trying to get them to chase me. I like to play fetch too if someone will play with me. And I love toys. I always have one with me. It takes me some time to warm up to new people and other animals. But once I do I won’t leave your side. I sleep with my foster mom in bed at night. And I’m house broke and crate trained. Car rides are very stressful for me and I bark and bark until I’m hoarse. Did I mention I’m deaf? I can’t hear anything. And because of that I need a securely fenced yard. I have a lot of prey drive so invisible fencing won’t work for me.  Rabbits, stray cats, squirrels and even birds don’t dare invade my yard. I don’t attend events because the commotion and all of the people stress me out. So if you’d like to meet me fill out the application and my foster mom will get a hold of you for a private meeting. My adoption fee is sponsored by an anonymous donor in honor of their beloved dog, Buzzy.

Please understand the statements about this animal are based upon the foster home's evaluation of the animal.  The animal might behave differently (negatively or positively) in your home.  While the animal might be good with the current foster’s dogs, cats, children, etc., it may not be with your animal(s) or children.  The animal may be housebroken or litter trained in the home of the foster but may relapse in your home.  The animal is represented to the public as it performs in the foster home and any statements made regarding the animal are conditional to that foster home setting.  Those interested in adopting should have read all information about the animal and understand they cannot claim they did not understand the facts about this animal as understood by Planned Pethood and/or the foster.  Planned Pethood and vet(s) do our best to provide accurate age and breed of the animal, but sometimes they are educated guesses.  Please understand that statements made regarding this animal are simply overviews and are not guaranteed.  Your adoption fee is non-refundable for any reason.

animal.description:
Adoption fee on this dog is $300.

Suarez is a handsome 3 to 5 year old sable male. He came to us through a local shelter so little is known of his background. He originally tested as heart-worm positive but has successfully completed his treatment.

While Suarez can be nervous in new environments and with new people, once he gets comfortable, this young boy is very affectionate and just wants to be with his humans. He loves car rides.

Suarez is always excited to go out for walks and walks well on a leash. He knows some basic commands such as sit and has learned to sit and wait for his food or to come in from outside. He is housebroken and crate trained. He has a dog door to go outside and has access to inside and outside all the time.

Suarez is an active boy with a lot of energy. He loves to run around and wrestle with the female Shepherd in his foster home. When excited, Suarez can be a little mouthy and doesn't quite understand that playing with humans is different than playing with other dogs. We recommend no children under the age of 12 for this boy. Suarez was very neck and collar sensitive when we got him and he would attempt to correct his human and do his best to get his way. This has gone away with a lot of training but he can still become defensive if he feels threatened. He will need to be muzzled and possibly sedated for nail trimming and vet visits.

This boy will do best with a strong handler who understands the need for constant, consistent leadership and who will continue his training, exercise and socialization. He would also love another active large dog to play with.

This dog is a Level 3. Please be sure you understand what a dog of this Level requires. Go to our home page for an explanation of the Dog Rating Levels.

For more information and to see when this dog will be attending an Adoption Day, please see our Dogs page on our main website at www.gcgsr.org. 

We operate within a reasonable driving distance from the Greater Sacramento area, the 	Central Valley down to Merced, and Lake Tahoe. A reasonable driving distance is determined by where one of our volunteers is willing to drive within our areas of service. That means we don't adopt out of our area, to Southern California, or Out of State. 


Thank you for visiting!

animal.description:
Breed: Shih Tzu
Age: 7 yrs.
Weight: 19 lbs.
Good with dogs: not right now
Good with cats: unsure
Good with kids:   no 
Energy level:  low to medium
Good with men/strangers:  no
Hypoallergenic: no

Special home requirements or medical:  Issues with his eyes. Impaired vision.  Needs an adult only home, calm environment

Additional info:  

This is a very heartbreaking story, so get your tissues ready. Aston was surrendered to the shelter extremely scared and matted, especially around his face.  When the shelter tried to cut away his hair he put up resistance.  They eventually had to sedate him and what they found under all that hair was, bulging, blood shot eyes. He had taken a pretty severe blow to the head which had affected his eyes and he has been on eye drops ever since.  

Aston has come such a long way and after a two and a half with us he is SO ready for his forever home! As much as we all love Aston, it's time for him to leave us. Aston still has some issues with trusting new people and it may take him a few weeks until he becomes comfortable enough with someone. We are sure these issues are a combination of the trauma that he experienced in his past and the fact that he's blind. The key to Aston's trust is to allow him some time to get to know your voice and smell, he must always know when you are going to touch him and this can easily be done by using your voice in a soft matter and allowing him to smell you first. Once he trusts you he has no issues with getting love and giving love, he will follow his person around like a little shadow but at the same time can be independent and is content just knowing you are in the room. He does not let his vision slow him down on walks and moves confidently with no issues when on leash. Because of Aston bite history and he can be overwhelmed in busy situations, so he cannot be around children and needs a calm environment in an adult only home, he prefers to have someone around often. A yard for Aston would be amazing as he loves to trot around and sunbathe.

If you are not ready to adopt just yet and would like to help in other ways, please consider clicking on the green “Sponsor Me” button above to help this dog receive the best care we can give. We rely on the generosity of others to make rescuing dogs possible.

IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS DOG, PLEASE MAKE SURE YOU HAVE READ THE DOG'S INFORMATION CAREFULLY.  ONCE YOU HAVE DONE SO, PLEASE DO THE FOLLOWING:
1.       Visit www.dogswithoutborders.org
2.      Then fill out an online ADOPTION APPLICATION -  http://dogswithoutborders.org/adopt-a-dog/adoption-application/
3.       Please wait to hear from our representative in approximately 48 hours on weekdays.
4.       To learn more about our adoption process, please look up our Adoption FAQ’s. - http://dogswithoutborders.org/adopt-a-dog/adoption-faq/

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Personality:
Kyle is new to our program but so far we know he is a bit anxious and will do best in a quieter home without a lot of distraction. Young children may be too much for him and he may appreciate a home as an only dog only so he can relax and enjoy all the attention. He's in a foster home with other dogs and does fine with them but again, seems anxious with all the hustle and bustle. Please check back for updates on Kyle as we learn more about him

None of our foster dogs are tested with cats because we have no way of testing them with cats. Siberians are notorious for their high prey drive and typically kill cats, rabbits, chickens, birds, squirrels, opossums, etc., so we we don't have much success adopting them out to homes with cats. Most of our foster dogs are with us for killing cats, chickens and goats to begin with so our assumption is they are not good with cats and other small things that move.

Siberians are typically good with children of all ages and the only reason we would not list them as not good with kids is because they may be too energetic and bouncy and knock over a toddler.

Southern Siberian Rescue is a volunteer based 501(c)3 organization based out of Raleigh, NC, so we do not have a physical facility with operating hours that you can visit to meet our dogs. All of our foster dogs are in our personal homes. You need to fill out our adoption application (http://www.southernsiberian.com/info/adoption) and get approved to adopt and then we will set a time for you to meet our foster dogs. As a volunteer based group, we all have jobs, family, personal dogs and other commitments but we try to acknowledge and process applications as quickly as we can. That being said, we try to keep our available foster dogs as current as we can also but it is time consuming to get pics and information on new dogs so not all of our dogs are listed at all times. Please fill out our application and then we can discuss dogs that will work for you and your situation. We average 40-45 Siberians in our program so we are certain we have one that will work for you. Please know that we are not obligated to answer inquiries on dogs as we will focus on approved applicants. Again, there is ample time to discuss all of our foster dogs AFTER we have an approved application on file. We do adopt out of state as long as we can get a home check done. We ask that you, your family and existing pets make the trip to NC to meet and adopt our foster dogs.

SSR can not and will not hold dogs for anyone. If we do, that means another Siberian will die in a shelter because a shelter dogs time is very limited, as is our foster space. We do our best to process applications in the order received and first application gets first interest in our foster dog(s). We understand that there will be scheduling conflicts with home checks and meet and greets but we will try to accommodate for that if a potential adopter has interest in a particular foster dog in our program.

All Southern Siberian Rescue foster dogs are microchipped, up to date on shots, spay/neutered, on monthly heartworm preventative and flea and tick preventative. For additional information on Southern Siberian Rescue and Siberian Huskies, please visit www.SouthernSiberian.com. To fill out an application, please visit

http://www.southernsiberian.com/info/adoption
